{"title_page": "Barbara Walters", "text_new": "{{short description|American broadcast journalist, author, and television personality}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image         = Barbara_Walters_2004.jpg\n| caption       = Walters in 2004\n| birth_name    = Barbara Jill Walters\n| birth_date    = {{nowrap|{{birth date and age|1929|09|25}}}}\n| birth_place   = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Journalist\n| years_active  = 1953\u20132016\n| alma_mater = [[Sarah Lawrence College]]\n| spouse        = {{Plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Robert Henry Katz|1955|1957|reason=annulled}}\n* {{marriage|[[Lee Guber]]|1963|1976|reason=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|[[Merv Adelson]]|1981|1984|reason=divorced}}<br>{{marriage||1986|1992|reason=divorced}}\n}}\n| children      = 1\n| credits       = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'' (1962\u201376)\n* ''[[ABC World News|ABC Evening News]]'' (1976\u201378)\n* ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'' (1979\u20132004)\n* ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'' (1997\u20132014)\n}}\n<!--| salary = $12 million (2007)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/53/07celebrities_Barbara-Walters_O4HQ.html|title=Barbara Walters|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=May 8, 2008|date=June 14, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509041247/http://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/53/07celebrities_Barbara-Walters_O4HQ.html|archivedate=May 9, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>-->\n}}\n\n'''Barbara Jill Walters''' (born September 25, 1929) is an American [[broadcast journalist]], author, and television personality.<ref name=\"Walters1\">{{cite news|title=Miss Walters engaged|page=96|work=The New York Times|date=May 1, 1955}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/barbara-walters/bio/194063|title=Barbara Walters: Biography|publisher=[[TV Guide|TVGuide.com]]|accessdate=February 3, 2014}}</ref> Respected for her interviewing ability and popularity with viewers, Walters appeared as the host of numerous television programs, including ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'', ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'', ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'', and the ''[[ABC World News|ABC Evening News]]''. Since retiring as a full-time host and contributor, she continued to occasionally report for [[ABC News]] through 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2013/05/barbara-walters-announces-2014-retirement/|title=Barbara Walters Announces 2014 Retirement \u2013 ABC News|publisher=Abcnews.go.com|date=May 12, 2013|accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-barbara-walters-retirement-peter-rodger-interview-20140610-story.html|title=Barbara Walters returns from retirement for Peter Rodger interview|work=LA Times|date=June 10, 2014|accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/donald-trump-responds-critics/story?id=35656421|title=Donald Trump Responds to Critics: Somebody 'Has to Say What's Right'|website=ABC News|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWalters began her career on ''[[The Today Show]]'' in the early 1960s as a writer and segment producer of women's interest stories. Her popularity with viewers resulted in Walters receiving more airtime, and in 1974 she became co-host of the program, the first woman to hold such a title on an American news program.<ref>{{cite book|last=Walters|first=Barbara|title=Audition: a memoir|year=2008|publisher=Knopf|location=NY|isbn=978-0-307-26646-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/205 205]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Walters|first=Barbara|title=Audition: a memoir|year=2008|publisher=Knopf|location=NY|isbn=978-0-307-26646-0|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Meaney, VP-TV News Programming|first=Donald|title=NBC-TV Press Release|date=April 22, 1974}}</ref> In 1976, she continued to be a pioneer for women in broadcasting by becoming the first female co-anchor of a network evening news program, alongside [[Harry Reasoner]] on the ''ABC Evening News''. From 1979 to 2004, Walters worked as a producer and co-host on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] newsmagazine ''20/20''. She also became known for an annual special aired on ABC, ''[[Barbara Walters' 10 Most Fascinating People]]''.\n\nWalters also created, produced, and co-hosted the ABC daytime talk show ''The View'', on which she appeared from 1997 until her retirement in 2014.<ref name=retirement>{{cite news |title=Walters to Announce 2014 Retirement on 'The View' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/13/business/media/barbara-walters-to-announce-2014-retirement-on-the-view.html?pagewanted=1&_r=2&hp& |accessdate=May 13, 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 13, 2013}}</ref> Thereafter, she continued to host a number of special reports for ''20/20'' as well as [[documentary]] series for [[Investigation Discovery]]. Her final on-air appearance for ABC News was in 2015.<ref name=\"adweek.com\">{{cite web |author=Chris Ariens |url=http://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/barbara-walters-return-to-2020-wins-the-hour-for-abc/260383 |title=Barbara Walters Return to 20/20 Wins the Hour for ABC &#124; TVNewser |publisher=Adweek.com |date=April 11, 2015 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes1\">{{cite web |url=https://latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-barbara-walters-retirement-peter-rodger-interview-20140610-story.html |title=Barbara Walters returns from retirement for Peter Rodger interview |work=LA Times |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"abcnews.go.com\">{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Press_Release/barbara-walters-interviews-presidential-candidate-donald-trump-family/story?id=35261113 |title=Barbara Walters Interviews Presidential Candidate Donald Trump And His Family \u2013 ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=November 17, 2015 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"press.discovery.com\">{{cite web|url=https://press.discovery.com/us/id/programs/american-scandal-barbara-walters/|title=Barbara Walters Presents American Scandals : Programs : Investigation Discovery : Discovery Press Web|website=press.discovery.com}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/barbara-walters-reveals-annual-fascinating-people-list/story?id=35512361 |title=Barbara Walters Reveals Her Annual 'Most Fascinating People' List \u2013 ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=December 2, 2015 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Walters was ranked #34 on the ''[[TV Guide]]'' \"50 Greatest TV Stars of All Time\" list,<ref>{{cite journal |year=1996 |title=Special Collectors' Issue: 50 Greatest TV Stars of All Time |journal=[[TV Guide]] |issue=December 14\u201320 }}</ref> and in 2000 she received a Lifetime Achievement Award from the [[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]].\n\n==Early life==\nBarbara Walters was born in 1929{{#tag:ref|Sources confirming her birth year in 1929:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Barbara_Walters.aspx |title=Barbara Walters Facts, information, pictures &#124; Encyclopedia.com articles about Barbara Walters |publisher=Encyclopedia.com |date= |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author= |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/12/05/us/barbara-walters---fast-facts/ |title=Barbara Walters Fast Facts |publisher=CNN.com |date=September 29, 2015 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://openlibrary.org/subjects/person:barbara_walters_(1931-) |title=Barbara Walters (1931-) |publisher=Open Library |date= |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=TheBiography.us |url=http://thebiography.us/en/walters-barbara |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415211224/http://thebiography.us/en/walters-barbara |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 15, 2016 |title=Biography of Barbara Walters (1931-VVVV) |publisher=TheBiography.us |date=October 2, 1931 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebritorium.com/celebrity-birthday/Barbara-Walters-date-of-birth-1931-09-25-1273.htm|title=Barbara Walters Birthday - September 25, 1931 - List of Celebrities & their Date of Birth @ Celebritorium.com|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://biography.yourdictionary.com/barbara-walters |title=Barbara Walters Facts |publisher=Biography.yourdictionary.com |date= |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/people/1478076?c=people |title=Walters, Barbara (1931-) \u2013 People and organisations \u2013 Trove |publisher=Trove.nla.gov.au |date= |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.almanac.com/fact/barbara-walters-newscaster-born |title=When was Barbara Walters (newscaster) born? &#124; Old Farmer's Almanac |publisher=Almanac.com |date=September 25, 1931 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.torontopubliclibrary.ca/detail.jsp?Entt=RDM2402423&R=2402423 |title=Audition : a memoir : Walters, Barbara, 1931- : Book, Regular Print Book : Toronto Public Library |publisher=Torontopubliclibrary.ca |date=May 13, 2008 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/barbara-walters |title=Barbara Walters Interview &#124; Archive of American Television |publisher=Emmytvlegends.org |date= |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>|group=\"sources\"}} (although Walters herself has claimed 1931 in an on-camera interview)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7M7pYKYu8-w#t=138 |title=Barbara Walters Interview Part 1 of 4 \u2013 EMMYTVLEGENDS.ORG |publisher=YouTube |date=August 28, 2009 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref> in [[Boston]] to Dena (n\u00e9e Seletsky) and [[Lou Walters|Louis \"Lou\" Walters]] (born Louis Abraham Warmwater).<ref>{{cite book |last=Walters |first=Barbara |title=Audition: a memoir |year=2008 |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |location=New York |isbn=978-0-307-26646-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/9 9] |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W |url-access=registration }}</ref><ref>Stated on ''Finding Your Roots'', PBS, April 1, 2012</ref> Her parents were both Jewish,<ref name=\"Walters3\">{{cite news |last=Quinn |first=Sally |title=Television Personality Looks Anew At Religion |work=[[The Washington Post]]/[[Newsweek]] |date=December 22, 2006 |url=http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/guestvoices/2006/12/television_personality_looks_a.html |accessdate=December 22, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070106163807/http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/guestvoices/2006/12/television_personality_looks_a.html |archivedate=January 6, 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> and descendants of refugees from the former [[Russian Empire]].<ref name=\"Audition\">{{cite book |title=Audition: A Memoir |last=Walters |first=Barbara |year=2008 |publisher=[[Alfred A. Knopf]] |location=New York |isbn=978-0-307-26646-0 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/7 7]\u201313 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W |url-access=registration }}</ref> Walters's paternal grandfather, Abraham Isaac Warmwater, was born in [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]], Poland, and emigrated to the United Kingdom, changing his name to Abraham Walters (the original family surname was Waremwasser).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/03/23/149222907/helping-celebrities-find-their-roots|title=Helping Celebrities Find Their Roots|publisher=}}</ref> Walters's father, Lou, was born in London c. 1896 and moved to New York with his father and two brothers, arriving August 28, 1909. His mother and four sisters arrived in 1910.<ref>{{cite book |last=Walters |first=Barbara |title=Audition: a memoir |year=2008 |publisher=Knopf |location=NY |isbn=978-0-307-26646-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/10 10] |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W |url-access=registration }}</ref> During her childhood her father managed the [[Latin Quarter (nightclub)|Latin Quarter]] nightclub. This club was owned in partnership with E.M. Loew and initially located in Boston, Massachusetts. In 1949, her father opened the New York version of the Latin Quarter. He also worked as a Broadway producer where he produced the ''[[Ziegfeld Follies]] of 1943''.<ref name=\"Walters2\">{{cite news |title=Lou Walters, Nightclub Impresario and Founder of Latin Quarter, Dies |page=36 |website=The New York Times |date=August 16, 1977}}</ref><ref>{{IBDB name|id=7381|name=Lou Walters}}</ref> He also was the Entertainment Director for the [[Tropicana Resort and Casino]] in Las Vegas, Nevada, where he imported the \"Folies Berg\u00e8re\" stage show from Paris to the resort's main showroom.<ref>[http://www.a2zlasvegas.com/hotels/history/h-trop.html Tropicana \u2013 Las Vegas Strip]. A2zlasvegas.com. Retrieved on October 27, 2011.</ref> Walters's brother, Burton, died in 1944 of [[pneumonia]].<ref name=\"Conaway\">James Conaway, \"How to talk with Barbara Walters about practically anything,\" ''The New York Times'', September 10, 1972, page SM40, 43\u201344</ref> Walters's elder sister, Jacqueline, was born [[Disabilities affecting intellectual abilities|mentally disabled]]<ref name=\"actors\">Stated in interview at ''[[Inside the Actors Studio]]''</ref> and died of [[ovarian cancer]] in 1985.\n\nAccording to Walters, her father made and lost several fortunes throughout his life in show business. He was a booking agent, and unlike her uncles who were in the shoe and dress business, his job was not very safe. During the good times, Walters recalls her father taking her to the rehearsals of the night club shows he directed and produced. The actresses and dancers would make a huge fuss over her and twirl her around until she was dizzy. Then she said her father would take her out for hot dogs, their favorite.<ref name=\"Walters, Barbara 2008\">Walters, Barbara (2008). ''Audition: A Memoir''. New York: Alfred A. Knopf</ref>\n\nAccording to Walters, being surrounded by celebrities when she was young kept her from being \"in awe\" of them.<ref name=\"actors\" /> When she was a young woman, Walters's father lost his night clubs and the family's [[Penthouse apartment|penthouse]] on [[Central Park West]]. As Walters recalled, \"He had a [[Mental breakdown|breakdown]]. He went down to live in our house in Florida, and then the government took the house, and they took the car, and they took the furniture.\" Of her mother, she said, \"My mother should have married the way her friends did, to a man who was a doctor or who was in the dress business.\"<ref name=\"Bumiller\">Elisabeth Bumiller, \"So Famous, Such Clout, She Could Interview Herself\", ''The New York Times'', April 21, 1996, page H1</ref>\n\nWalters attended Lawrence School, a public school in Brookline, Massachusetts, to the middle of fifth grade, when her father moved the family to Miami Beach in 1939, where she also attended public school. After her father moved the family to New York City, she went to eighth grade at [[Ethical Culture Fieldston School]], after which the family moved back to Miami Beach. Then, she went back to New York City, where she attended [[Birch Wathen Lenox|Birch Wathen School]]<ref name=\"New York Magazine\">[https://nymag.com/news/features/28519/index1.html \"Can Barbara Walters's Career Survive Rosie and Donald's War?\"] ''New York'' (March 5, 2007). Retrieved on October 27, 2011.</ref><ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/25/books/and-now-back-to-you-barbara.html |work=The New York Times |title=And Now Back to You, Barbara |first=Maureen |last=Dowd |date=March 25, 1990 |accessdate=April 26, 2010}}</ref> from which she graduated in 1947. In 1951 she received a B.A. in English from [[Sarah Lawrence College]]<ref name=\"biography.com\">{{cite web |title=Barbara Walters Biography |publisher=biography.com |url=http://www.biography.com/people/barbara-walters-9523127}}</ref> and immediately looked for work in New York City. After about a year at a small advertising agency, she began working at the NBC network affiliate in New York City, WNBT-TV (now [[WNBC]]), doing publicity and writing press releases. She began producing a 15-minute children's program, ''Ask the Camera'', directed by [[Roone Arledge]] in 1953. She began producing for TV host [[Igor Cassini]]/[[Cholly Knickerbocker]]. However, she left the network after her boss pressured her to marry him and engaged in a fist-fight with a man she preferred to date. Then she went to WPIX to produce the ''Eloise McElhone Show''; it was canceled in 1954. She became a writer on ''The Morning Show'' at [[CBS]] in 1955.\n\n==Career==\n\n===''The Today Show''===\n[[File:Today show panel 1973.JPG|thumb|[[Gene Shalit]], Barbara Walters, and [[Frank McGee (journalist)|Frank McGee]] in ''The Today Show'', 1973.]]\nAfter a few years as a publicist with [[Tex McCrary]] Inc. and a job as a writer at [[Redbook]] magazine, Walters joined [[NBC]]'s ''[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]]'' as a writer and researcher in 1961.<ref name=\"actors\" /> She moved up to become that show's regular \"Today Girl,\" handling lighter assignments and the weather. In her autobiography, she describes this era before the [[Feminism|Women's Movement]] as a time when it was believed that nobody would take a woman seriously reporting \"hard news.\" Previous [[Today (NBC program)#Today Girls|\"Today Girls\"]] (whom Walters called \"tea pourers\") included [[Florence Henderson]], [[Helen O'Connell]], [[Estelle Parsons]] and [[Lee Meriwether]].<ref>''Audition'', pp. 107\u2013114</ref> Within a year, she had become a reporter-at-large developing, writing, and editing her own reports and interviews. One very well received film segment was \"A Day in the Life of a Novice Nun,\" edited by then-first assistant film editor Donald Swerdlow (now Don Canaan), who was subsequently promoted to become a full film editor at NBC News.<ref name=\"actors\" /> She had a great relationship with host Hugh Downs for years. When [[Frank McGee (journalism)|Frank McGee]] was named host, he refused to do joint interviews with Walters unless he was given the first three questions. She was not named co-host of the show until McGee's death in 1974 when NBC officially designated Walters as the program's first female co-host. Beginning in 1971, she also hosted her own local NBC affiliate show, ''[[Not for Women Only]],'' which ran in the mornings after ''The Today Show.''<ref name=\"thompson\">{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Kathleen |title=Barbara Walters |url=https://jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/walters-barbara |website=Jewish Women's Archive |publisher=Jewish Women's Archive |accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>''Audition'', p. 190</ref>\n\n[[File:Barbara Walters \u00a9Lynn Gilbert.gif|thumb|Barbara Walters in her office, as photographed by [[Lynn Gilbert]] in 1979.]]\n\n===''ABC Evening News'' and ''20/20''===\nWalters has seldom minced words when describing the visible, on-the-air disdain her co-anchor [[Harry Reasoner]] displayed for her when she was teamed up with him on the ''[[ABC Evening News]]'' from 1976\u201378. Reasoner had a difficult relationship with Walters, because he disliked having a co-anchor, even though he worked with former CBS colleague [[Howard K. Smith]] nightly on ABC for several years. In 1981, five years after the start of their short-lived ABC partnership and well after Reasoner returned to CBS News, Walters and her former co-anchor had a memorable (and cordial) ''20/20'' interview on the occasion of Reasoner's new book release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.today.com/popculture/barbara-walters-legendary-career-offers-view-back-today-2D79669608|title=Barbara Walters' legendary career offers a 'View' back to TODAY|website=TODAY.com|language=en|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWalters is also known for her years on the ABC newsmagazine ''20/20'' where she reunited with former ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today Show]]'' host [[Hugh Downs]] in 1979.<ref name=\"actors\" /> Throughout her career at ABC, Walters has appeared on ABC news specials as a commentator, including presidential inaugurations and the coverage of [[9/11]]. She was also chosen to be the moderator for the third and final debate between candidates [[Jimmy Carter]] and [[Gerald Ford]], held on the campus of the College of William and Mary at [[Phi Beta Kappa Memorial Hall]] in [[Williamsburg, Virginia]], during the [[1976 United States presidential election|1976 presidential election]].<ref name=CNN>[https://web.archive.org/web/20001006083517/http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2000/debates/history.story/1976.html CNN: 1976 Presidential Debates]. Retrieved on June 14, 2008.</ref> In 1984, she moderated a Presidential debate held at the Dana Center for the Humanities at [[Saint Anselm College]] in [[Goffstown, New Hampshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VkIsAAAAIBAJ&pg=3623,1412416&dq=barbara%20walters%20saint%20anselm&hl=en|title=Herald-Journal - Google News Archive Search|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n====Interviews====\n[[File:Barbara Walters-The Fords.jpg|right|thumb|Walters interviewing President [[Gerald Ford]] and [[Betty Ford]] in 1976.]]\n\nWalters is known for \"personality journalism\" and her \"scoop\" interviews.<ref name=\"actors\" /> In November 1977, she achieved a joint interview with Egypt's President, [[Anwar Al Sadat]], and Israel's Prime Minister, [[Menachem Begin]]. According to ''The New York Times'', when she went mano a mano with Walter Cronkite to interview both world leaders, at the end of Cronkite's interview, he is clearly heard saying: \"Did Barbara get anything I didn't get?\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Maselin|first= J. |date=May 5, 2008|title=Hard sell, soft touch, and the right question|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/05/books/05masl.html?_r=1&}}</ref> Her interviews with world leaders from all walks of life are a chronicle of the latter part of the 20th century.<ref name=\"actors\" /> They include the [[Pahlavi dynasty|Shah of Iran]], [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]], and his wife, the Empress [[Farah Pahlavi]]; Russia's [[Boris Yeltsin]] and [[Vladimir Putin]]; China's [[Jiang Zemin]]; the UK's [[Margaret Thatcher]]; Cuba's [[Fidel Castro]], as well as India's [[Indira Gandhi]], Czechoslovakia's [[V\u00e1clav Havel]], Libya's [[Muammar al-Gaddafi]], King [[Hussein of Jordan]], King [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia]], and Venezuelan President [[Hugo Chavez]], among many others. Other interviews with influential people include pop icon [[Michael Jackson]], actress [[Katharine Hepburn]], ''Vogue'' editor [[Anna Wintour]], and in 1980 [[Laurence Olivier|Sir Laurence Olivier]]. Walters considered [[Robert Smithdas]], a deaf-blind man who spent his life improving the lives of other individuals who are deaf-blind, as her most inspirational interview.\n\nWalters was widely lampooned for asking actress [[Katharine Hepburn]], \"If you were a tree, what kind would you be?\" On her last 20/20 television episode, Walters showed video of the Hepburn interview, showing the actress saying that she would like to be a tree. Walters merely followed up with the question, \"What kind of a tree?\",<ref name=\"actors\" /><ref>[http://katethegreatnet.proboards.com/index.cgi?board=tv&action=display&thread=1133561741 Kate the Great, The Katharine Hepburn Forum \u2013 The Barbara Walters Interview] Retrieved May 10, 2008{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2008|accessdate=May 8, 2008}}</ref> and Hepburn responded \"an oak\" because they are strong and pretty. According to Walters, for years Hepburn refused her requests for an interview. And when she finally agreed to one, she said she wanted to meet her first. Walters walked in all smiles and ready to please, while Hepburn was at the top of the stairs and barked, \"You're late. Have you brought me chocolates?\" Walters hadn't but said she never showed up without them from then on. They had several other meetings since that first time, mostly in Hepburn's living room where she would give Walters her opinions. Careers and marriage did not mix. Children and careers were out of the question. Walters said Hepburn's opinions stuck with her so much, she could repeat them almost verbatim to this day.<ref name=\"Walters, Barbara 2008\" />\n\nHer television special about Cuban leader [[Fidel Castro]] aired on ABC-TV on June 9, 1977. Although the footage of her two days of interviewing Castro in Cuba showed his personality, in part, as freewheeling, charming, and humorous,<ref>{{cite book |last=Walters |first=Barbara |title=Audition: a memoir |year=2008 |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |location=New York |isbn=978-0-307-26646-0 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/324 324]\u2013333 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W |url-access=registration }}</ref> she pointedly said to him, \"You allow no dissent. Your newspapers, radio, television, motions picture are under state control.\" To this, he replied, \"Barbara, our concept of freedom of the press is not yours. If you asked us if a newspaper could appear here against socialism, I can say honestly no, it cannot appear. It would not be allowed by the party, the government, or the people. In that sense we do not have the freedom of the press that you possess in the U.S. And we are very satisfied about that.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Walters |first=Barbara |title=Audition: a memoir |year=2008 |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |location=New York |isbn=978-0-307-26646-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/327 327] |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W |url-access=registration }}</ref> She concluded the broadcast of the interview by remarking, \"What we disagreed on most profoundly is the meaning of freedom\u2014and that is what truly separates us.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Walters |first=Barbara |title=Audition: a memoir |year=2008 |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |location=New York |isbn=978-0-307-26646-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/329 329] |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W |url-access=registration }}</ref> At the time, Walters kept quiet about seeing New York Yankees owner [[George Steinbrenner]], pitcher [[Whitey Ford]], and several coaches in Cuba, there to assist Cuban ballplayers.\n\nOn March 3, 1999, her interview of [[Monica Lewinsky]] was seen by a record 74 million viewers, the highest rating ever for a news program.<ref>{{cite web |last=de Moraes |first=Lisa |title=Monica Lewinsky Beats the Competition |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/tv030599.htm |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=May 12, 2013 |date=March 5, 1999}}</ref> Walters asked Lewinsky, \"What will you tell your children when you have them?\" Lewinsky replied, \"Mommy made a big mistake,\" at which point Walters brought the program to a dramatic conclusion, turning to the viewers and saying, \"And that is the understatement of the year.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Shales |first=Tom |title=Once More, With Feeling |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/shales030499.htm |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=May 12, 2013 |date=March 4, 1999}}</ref>\n\n===''The View''===\n[[File:Barack Obama guests on The View.jpg|thumb|right|''The View's'' panel (left\u2013right [[Whoopi Goldberg]], Barbara Walters, [[Joy Behar]], [[Sherri Shepherd]] and [[Elisabeth Hasselbeck]]) interview [[United States President]] [[Barack Obama]] on July 29, 2010.]]\n{{Main|The View (talk show)}}\n\nWalters was a co-host of the daytime talk show ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]],'' of which she also is co-creator and co-executive producer with her business partner, [[Bill Geddie]]. It premiered on August 11, 1997.<ref name=\"actors\" />\n\nWalters described the show in its original opening credits as a forum for women of \"different generations, backgrounds, and views.\" She added, \"Be careful what you wish for...\" on the opening credits of its second season. Through ''The View'', she was able to clinch two [[Daytime Emmy Award]]s for Best Talk Show in 2003 and Best Talk Show Host (with longtime host [[Joy Behar]], moderator [[Whoopi Goldberg]], [[Elisabeth Hasselbeck]], and [[Sherri Shepherd]]) in 2009.\n\nWalters retired from being a co-host on May 15, 2014. Although retired, Walters returned as a guest co-host on an intermittent basis throughout 2014 and 2015.\n\n===Retirement===\nSince leaving her role as ''20/20'' co-host in 2004, Walters remained as a part-time contributor of special programming and interviews for [[ABC News]] until 2016.\n\nOn March 7, 2010, Barbara Walters announced she would no longer hold Oscar interviews, but will still be working with ABC and on ''The View.''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/oscars/7393741/Barbara-Walters-to-host-last-Oscars-special-amid-overexposure-of-stars.html |title=Barbara Walters to host last Oscars special amid 'overexposure' of stars |accessdate=March 8, 2010 |last=Allen |first=Nick |date=March 7, 2010 |work=Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited 2010 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn a November 2010 episode of ''The View'', while interviewing [[Larry King]] on his retirement from CNN, Walters alluded to her impending retirement, stating, \"I know when my time's coming.\"\n\nOn March 28, 2013, numerous media outlets reported that Barbara Walters would retire in May 2014 and that she would make the announcement on the show four days later.<ref name=\"NYT Carter Walter nearing retirement\">{{cite news |last=Carter |first=Bill |title=Barbara Walters Said to Be Nearing Retirement |url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/28/barbara-walters-said-to-be-nearing-retirement/ |accessdate=April 17, 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=March 28, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"WP Walters to announce retiring\">{{cite news |last=de Moraes |first=Lisa |title=Barbara Walters to announce she's retiring \u2014 next year |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/tv-column/post/barbara-walters-to-announce-shes-retiring--next-year/2013/03/28/c6d7d296-97f4-11e2-b68f-dc5c4b47e519_blog.html |accessdate=April 17, 2013 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 28, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Baltimore Sun Walter retiring\">{{cite news |last=Zurawik |first=David |title=Barbara Walters retiring after 52 years in television |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-03-28/entertainment/bal-barbara-walters-retiring-after-52-years-in-television-20130328_1_co-anchor-barbara-walters-harry-reasoner |accessdate=April 17, 2013 |newspaper=The Baltimiore Sun |date=March 28, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"MSNBC Walters trailblazer\">{{cite news |last=Whitaker |first=Morgan |title=Barbara Walters, TV trailblazer, set to retire |url=http://tv.msnbc.com/2013/03/30/barbara-walters-tv-trailblazer-set-to-retire/ |accessdate=April 17, 2013 |newspaper=MSNBC |date=March 30, 2013}}</ref> However, on the April 1 episode, Walters neither confirmed nor denied the retirement rumors; she said \"if and when I might have an announcement to make, I will do it on this program, I promise, and the paparazzi guys -- you will be the last to know\".<ref name=\"Newsday Walters no denial\">{{cite news |last=Gay |first=Verne |title=Barbara Walters on retirement: No comment, but no denial either |url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/tv-zone-1.811968/barbara-walters-on-retirement-no-comment-but-no-denial-either-1.4983373 |accessdate=April 17, 2013 |newspaper=Newsday |date=April 1, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"LA Times Walters no retirement\">{{cite news |last=Day |first=Patrick Kevin |title='The View's' Barbara Walters has no retirement announcement yet |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-the-views-barbara-walters-has-no-retirement-announcement-yet-20130401,0,5460912.story |accessdate=April 17, 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=April 1, 2013}}</ref> Walters confirmed six weeks later that she would be retiring from television hosting and interviewing in May 2014, as originally reported; she made the official announcement on the May 13, 2013, episode of ''The View'' while also announcing that she will continue as the show's executive producer for as long as it's on the air.<ref name=\"NYT Walters to Announce\">{{cite news |last=Carter |first=Bill |title=Walters to Announce 2014 Retirement on 'The View' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/13/business/media/barbara-walters-to-announce-2014-retirement-on-the-view.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 |accessdate=May 13, 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Chicago Tribune BW to announce\">{{cite news |title=Barbara Walters to announce retirement on \"The View,\" says ABC |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/sns-rt-us-barbarawaltersbre94c02u-20130512,0,3784948.story |accessdate=May 13, 2013 |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=May 12, 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"USA Today BW retirement\">{{cite news |last=Schwartz |first=Bruce |title=Barbara Walters will announce retirement |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2013/05/12/barbara-walters-will-announce-retirement/2154541/ |accessdate=May 13, 2013 |newspaper=USA Today |date=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN BW to retire\">{{cite news |last=Ford |first=Dana |title=Barbara Walters to retire next year |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/05/12/showbiz/barbara-walters-retirement/?hpt=hp_t2 |accessdate=May 13, 2013 |newspaper=CNN |date=May 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"LA Times Groundbreaking\">{{cite news |last=Villarreal |first=Yvonne |title=Groundbreaking TV journalist Barbara Walters is set to retire |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-groundbreaking-tv-journalist-barbara-walters-set-to-hang-it-up-20130512,0,4654559.story |accessdate=May 13, 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=May 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 10, 2014, it was announced that she would be 'coming out of retirement' in order to do a special 20/20 interview with [[Peter Rodger]], the father of Elliot Rodger who had committed the [[2014 Isla Vista killings]].<ref name=\"latimes1\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://jewishbusinessnews.com/2014/06/11/barbara-walters-is-already-set-to-interview-again-less-than-one-month-after-formally-retiring/ |title=Barbara Walters is Already Set to Interview Again Less Than One Month After Formally Retiring \u2013 Jewish Business News |publisher=Jewishbusinessnews.com |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSince then, she has hosted special ''20/20'' episodes featuring interviews with [[Mary Kay Letourneau]]<ref name=\"adweek.com\" /> and [[Donald Trump|Donald]] and [[Melania Trump]].<ref name=\"abcnews.go.com\" />\n\nIn 2015, Walters hosted the documentary series ''American Scandals'' on [[Investigation Discovery]].<ref name=\"press.discovery.com\" />\n\nWalters continued to host her [[Barbara Walters' 10 Most Fascinating People|10 Most Fascinating People]] series in 2014<ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2014/10/barbara-walters-presents-the-10-most-fascinating-people-of-2014-returns-to-abc-primetime-december-14-9-11-pm-et/ |title=\"BARBARA WALTERS PRESENTS: THE 10 MOST FASCINATING PEOPLE OF 2014,\" RETURNS TO ABC PRIMETIME DECEMBER 14, 9-11 PM ET \u2013 ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=October 21, 2014 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref> and 2015.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\nHer final on-air interview was of presidential candidate Donald Trump for ABC News in December 2015.<ref>{{cite web |author=Lisa de Moraes |url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/donald-trump-barbara-walters-not-bigot-muslim-ban-plan-video-1201660700/ |title=[VIDEO&#93; Donald Trump Tells Barbara Walters \"I'm Not A Bigot,\" Clearing That Up |publisher=Deadline |date=December 8, 2015 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWalters last appeared publicly in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barbara's Secret Struggle! 'Gravely' Ill Walters Not Seen In Public For 130 Days|url= https://www.radaronline.com/exclusives/2016/11/barbara-walters-dying-fears-the-view/|publisher=radaronline.com|accessdate=February 9, 2019|date= November 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=closer>{{Cite web|url=https://www.closerweekly.com/posts/where-is-barbara-walters-142633/|title=Where is Barbara Walters?|first=Samantha|last=Fagarelli|work=[[Closer (magazine)|closer]]|date=October 19, 2019|access-date=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWalters has been married four times to three different men. Her first husband was Robert Henry Katz, a business executive and former Navy lieutenant. They married on June 20, 1955, at [[Plaza Hotel|The Plaza Hotel]] in New York City.<ref name=\"Walters1\" /><ref>\"Katz\u2014Walters\", ''The New York Times'', June 21, 1955, page 36</ref> The marriage was reportedly annulled after 11 months,<ref>{{cite news |title=Top-Drawer Life of Barbara Walters |newspaper=Beaver County Times |location=Pennsylvania |date=October 7, 1974 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2002&dat=19741007&id=qvsqAAAAIBAJ&pg=886,1378488}}</ref> or in 1957.<ref>{{cite news |title=Walter's fiance is a man of few words, big bucks |newspaper=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=June 18, 1985 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB7C18EDD9D9D82&p_field_direct-0=document_id}}</ref>\n\nHer second husband was [[Lee Guber]], theatrical producer and theater owner. They married on December 8, 1963, and divorced in 1976. They have one daughter, Jacqueline Dena Guber (born 1968, adopted the same year).\n\nHer third husband was Merv Adelson, the CEO of [[Lorimar]] Television. They married in 1981 and divorced in 1984. They remarried in 1986 and divorced for the second time in 1992.\n\nShe dated lawyer<ref name=miller>{{cite book|last=Miller |first=Neil |title=Out of the Past: Gay and Lesbian History from 1869 to the Present |publisher=Advocate Books |year=2005 |pages=Ch. 18 |url=http://www2.english.uiuc.edu/finnegan/English%20256/Miller.htm |isbn=1-55583-870-7 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090902224218/http://www2.english.uiuc.edu/finnegan/English%20256/Miller.htm |archivedate=September 2, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wolfe |first=Tom |authorlink=Tom Wolfe |title=Dangerous Obsessions |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 3, 1988 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/04/03/books/dangerous-obsessions.html?pagewanted=print}}</ref> [[Roy Cohn]] in college; he said that he proposed marriage to Walters the night before her wedding to Lee Guber, but Walters denied this.<ref name=\"Conaway\" /> She explained her lifelong devotion to Cohn as gratitude for his help in her adoption of her daughter, Jacqueline.<ref name=\"Oppenheimer\">{{citation |author=Jerry Oppenheimer |title=Barbara Walters: An Unauthorized Biography |publisher=St. Martin's Press |year=1990}}</ref> In her autobiography, Walters says she also felt grateful to Cohn because of his legal assistance to her father. According to Walters, her father was the subject of an arrest warrant for \"failure to appear\" after he failed to show up for a New York court date because the family was in Las Vegas, and Cohn was able to have the charge dismissed.<ref name=\"Wiegand\">{{Cite news |last=Wiegand |first=David |title=Barbara Walters gets personal. This time, she's candid about her own life. |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |date=May 5, 2008 |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/05/05/DDTU10H1P9.DTL}}</ref> Walters testified as a character witness at Cohn's 1986 disbarment trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2017/06/donald-trump-roy-cohn-relationship|title=How Donald Trump and Roy Cohn's Ruthless Symbiosis Changed America|first=Marie|last=Brenner|publisher=|accessdate=August 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWalters dated future U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman [[Alan Greenspan]] in the 1970s<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/09232007/business/listen_to_shiller__not_the_tv_.htm |title=LISTEN TO SHILLER, NOT THE TV SHILLS |author=Terry Keenan |work=New York Post |date=September 23, 2007 |accessdate=October 13, 2007}}</ref> and was linked romantically to United States Senator [[John Warner]] in the\n1990s.\n\nIn Walters's autobiography ''Audition'', she claimed that she had an affair in the 1970s with [[Edward Brooke]], then a married [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] from Massachusetts. It is not clear whether Walters also was married at the time. Walters said they ended the affair to protect their careers from scandal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barbara Walters: I had affair with U.S. senator |url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/books/05/01/tv.walters.affair.ap/index.html|url-status=dead |work=CNN |agency=Associated Press (AP) |date=May 1, 2008| archivedate=May 2, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502133009/http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/books/05/01/tv.walters.affair.ap/index.html}}</ref> In 2007 she dated [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning gerontologist [[Robert Neil Butler]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secondact.com/2010/07/friends-of-robert-butler-describe/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105073845/http://www.secondact.com/2010/07/friends-of-robert-butler-describe/|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 5, 2011|title=The Father of Geriatrics Acted Anything But Old - Ageism - SecondAct.com|date=January 5, 2011|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWalters is close friends with [[Tom Brokaw]] and [[Woody Allen]], and was close friends with [[Joan Rivers]] as well with former [[Fox News]] head [[Roger Ailes]] from the late 1960s until his death in 2017.<ref>Fehrman, Craig (January 21, 2011) [http://www.salon.com/news/politics/war_room/2011/01/21/roger_ailes_fehrman/index.html When Roger Ailes was honest about what he does] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228232838/http://www.salon.com/news/politics/war_room/2011/01/21/roger_ailes_fehrman/index.html |date=February 28, 2011 }}, ''[[Salon.com]]''</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Walters appeared on CNN's ''[[Piers Morgan Live]]'' and revealed that not having more children is her greatest regret in life.<ref>{{YouTube|TwBFDnN97D0}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Barbara Walters: \"I Regret Not Having More Children\" |date=December 18, 2013 |website=The Huffington Post |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/12/18/barbara-walters-regret-children_n_4467162.html}}</ref>\n\n===Health===\nWalters announced on the May 10, 2010, episode of ''The View'' that she would be undergoing [[open heart surgery]] to replace a faulty [[aortic valve]]. She added that she knew for quite a while that she was suffering from [[aortic valve stenosis]], even though she was symptom-free. The procedure to fix the faulty heart valve \"went well, and the doctors are very pleased with the outcome,\" Walters's spokeswoman, Cindi Berger, said in a statement on May 14, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2010/05/14/barbara_walters_heart_valve_surgery_went_well/ |title=Barbara Walters' heart valve surgery 'went well' |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=May 14, 2010 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=April 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn July 9, 2010, it was announced that Walters would return to ''The View'' and her [[Sirius XM]] satellite show, ''Here's Barbara'', in September 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radio-info.com/news/making-moves-thursday-july-8-2010 |title=Making Moves: Thursday, July 8, 2010 |date=July 8, 2010 |work=Radio-Info.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714170331/http://www.radio-info.com/news/making-moves-thursday-july-8-2010 |archivedate=July 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/Barbara-Walters-Returns-to-prnews-1477182584.html?x=0&.v=1 |title=Barbara Walters Returns to Media Hosting Her Weekly SIRIUS XM Radio Show on July 12 |work=[[Yahoo! Finance]]}}{{Dead link|date=September 2012}}</ref>\n\nFour years later, Walters retired permanently from both shows.<ref>{{cite web|title='The View' co-hosts through the years: Barbara Walters, Whoopi Goldberg and more|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/the-view-hosts-1.8695392|publisher=newsday.com|accessdate=February 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nBarbara Walters was inducted into the [[Television Hall of Fame]] in 1989. On June 15, 2007, Walters received a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]. She has won Daytime and Prime Time Emmy Awards, a [[Women in Film Crystal + Lucy Awards|Women in Film Lucy Award]], and a [[GLAAD]] Excellence in Media award. Her impact on popular culture is illustrated by [[Gilda Radner]]'s \"Baba Wawa\" impersonation of her on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'',<ref name=\"actors\" /> featuring her idiosyncratic speech with its [[Rhotacism (speech impediment)|rounded \"R\"]]. Her name also appeared in the January 23, 1995 ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' Monday [[Crossword|Crossword Puzzle]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/crosswords/game/daily/1995/01/23|title=The Crossword|last=Robbins|first=Sidney L.|date=January 23, 1995|editor-last=Shortz|editor-first=Will|website=New York Times|url-status=live|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In 2008, she was honored with the [[Disney Legends]] award, given to those who made an outstanding contribution to [[The Walt Disney Company]], which owns the network [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]. That same year, she received the Lifetime Achievement Award from the [[New York Women's Agenda]]. On September 21, 2009, Walters was honored with a Lifetime Achievement Award at the 30th Annual News and Documentary Emmy Awards at New York City's Lincoln Center.\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{more citations needed|section|date=September 2017}}<!--Emmys and NAACP Image Awards are not cited-->\n* 1985: [[Paul White (journalist)|Paul White]] Award, [[Radio Television Digital News Association]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rtdna.org/content/paul_white_award#.U4FBHS8-Ngc |title=Paul White Award |publisher=[[Radio Television Digital News Association]] |accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n[[Daytime Emmy Awards]]\n* '''1975 Award for Daytime Emmy for Outstanding Talk Show Host (''Today'')'''\n* 1998 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 1998 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 1999 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 1999 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 2000 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 2000 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 2001 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 2001 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 2002 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 2002 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* '''2003 Award for Best Talk Show (''The View'')'''\n* 2003 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 2006 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 2006 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 2007 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 2007 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 2008 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 2008 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* '''2009 Award for Daytime Emmy for Outstanding Talk Show Host (''The View'')''' (with Whoopi Goldberg, Joy Behar, Elisabeth Hasselbeck and Sherri Shepherd)\n* 2010 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n\n[[NAACP Image Award]]\n* '''2009 Award for Best Talk Series (''The View'')'''\n* 2010 Nomination for Best Talk Series\n\n[[Women in Film Los Angeles|Women in Film]] [[Women in Film Crystal + Lucy Awards|Crystal + Lucy Award]]\n* 1998 [[Women in Film Crystal + Lucy Awards#THE LUCY AWARD|Lucy Award]] in recognition of her excellence and innovation in her creative works that have enhanced the perception of women through the medium of television.<ref>[http://wif.org/past-recipients Past Recipients] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724120329/http://www.wif.org/past-recipients |date=July 24, 2011 }}. Wif.org. Retrieved on October 27, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Books==\nIn the late 1960s, Walters wrote a magazine article, \"How to Talk to Practically Anyone About Practically Anything\", which drew upon the kinds of things people said to her, which were often mistakes.<ref name=\"Memoir186-189\">''Audition: A Memoir'', pp. 186\u20139</ref> Shortly after the article appeared, she received a letter from [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] expressing interest in expanding it into a book. Walters felt that it would help \"tongue-tied, socially awkward people\u2014the many people who worry that they can't think of the right thing to say to start a conversation.\"<ref name=\"Memoir186-189\" /> She published the book ''How to Talk with Practically Anybody about Practically Anything'' in 1970, with the assistance of [[ghostwriter]] [[June Callwood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.cbc.ca/arts_entertainment/media/topics/1393-8719/ |title=June Callwood interview by Patrick Watson |date=September 21, 1979 |accessdate=October 18, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521164734/http://archives.cbc.ca/arts_entertainment/media/topics/1393-8719/ |archivedate=May 21, 2011 }}</ref> To Walters's great surprise, the book was a success. As of 2008, it had gone through eight printings, sold hundreds of thousands of copies worldwide, and had been translated into at least six languages.<ref name=\"Memoir186-189\" />\n\nShe published her autobiography, ''[[Audition: A Memoir]]'', in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/05/books/05masl.html |title='Audition: A Memoir' by Barbara Walters |first=Janet |last=Maslin |date=May 5, 2008 |accessdate=December 17, 2016 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Barbara Walters' 10 Most Fascinating People]]\n* [[New Yorkers in journalism]]\n\n== Notes ==\n=== Explanatory notes ===\n{{reflist|group=sources}}\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite book |title=Seen and Heard: The Women of Television News |first=Nichola D. |last=Gutgold |publisher=Lexington Books |year=2008}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|910181|Barbara Walters}}\n* [https://abcnews.go.com/search?searchtext=time%20tunnel&from=0&to=9&type=video ABC News' \"Time Tunnel\" page containing clips of numerous newscasts on which Walters appeared]\n* [https://www.amazon.com/dp/B002KAOS24 Excerpts from 2008 autobiography, ''Audition: A Memoir'']\n* [http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/barbara-walters Barbara Walters Archive of American Television Interview]\n* [http://www.makers.com/barbara-walters Barbara Walters] Video produced by ''[[Makers: Women Who Make America]]''\n\n{{ABC News Personalities}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Barbara Walters\n|list =\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Lifetime Achievement}}\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Talk Show Host}}\n{{TCA Career Achievement Award}}\n{{1989 Television Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n\n{{portal bar|Biography|Journalism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walters, Barbara}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:ABC News personalities]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American television news anchors]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:American women television journalists]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Talk Show Host winners]]\n[[Category:Ethical Culture Fieldston School alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American journalists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish women writers]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Miami Beach Senior High School alumni]]\n[[Category:NBC News people]]\n[[Category:People from Brookline, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People with dementia]]\n[[Category:Sarah Lawrence College alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Boston]]\n[[Category:Writers from Miami]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Women memoirists]]\n[[Category:Women television writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Birch Wathen Lenox School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American broadcast journalist, author, and television personality}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image         = Barbara_Walters_2004.jpg\n| caption       = Walters in 2004\n| birth_name    = Barbara Jill Walters\n| birth_date    = {{nowrap|{{birth date and age|1929|09|25}}}}\n| birth_place   = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Journalist\n| years_active  = 1953\u20132016\n| alma_mater = [[Sarah Lawrence College]]\n| spouse        = {{Plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Robert Henry Katz|1955|1957|reason=annulled}}\n* {{marriage|[[Lee Guber]]|1963|1976|reason=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|[[Merv Adelson]]|1981|1984|reason=divorced}}<br>{{marriage||1986|1992|reason=divorced}}\n}}\n| children      = 1\n| credits       = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'' (1962\u201376)\n* ''[[ABC World News|ABC Evening News]]'' (1976\u201378)\n* ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'' (1979\u20132004)\n* ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'' (1997\u20132014)\n}}\n<!--| salary = $12 million (2007)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/53/07celebrities_Barbara-Walters_O4HQ.html|title=Barbara Walters|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=May 8, 2008|date=June 14, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509041247/http://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/53/07celebrities_Barbara-Walters_O4HQ.html|archivedate=May 9, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>-->\n}}\n\n'''Barbara Jill Walters''' (born September 25, 1929) is an American [[broadcast journalist]], author, and television personality.<ref name=\"Walters1\">{{cite news|title=Miss Walters engaged|page=96|work=The New York Times|date=May 1, 1955}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/barbara-walters/bio/194063|title=Barbara Walters: Biography|publisher=[[TV Guide|TVGuide.com]]|accessdate=February 3, 2014}}</ref> Respected for her interviewing ability and popularity with viewers, Walters appeared as the host of numerous television programs, including ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'', ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'', ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'', and the ''[[ABC World News|ABC Evening News]]''. Since retiring as a full-time host and contributor, she continued to occasionally report for [[ABC News]] through 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2013/05/barbara-walters-announces-2014-retirement/|title=Barbara Walters Announces 2014 Retirement \u2013 ABC News|publisher=Abcnews.go.com|date=May 12, 2013|accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-barbara-walters-retirement-peter-rodger-interview-20140610-story.html|title=Barbara Walters returns from retirement for Peter Rodger interview|work=LA Times|date=June 10, 2014|accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/donald-trump-responds-critics/story?id=35656421|title=Donald Trump Responds to Critics: Somebody 'Has to Say What's Right'|website=ABC News|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWalters began her career on ''[[The Today Show]]'' in the early 1960s as a writer and segment producer of women's interest stories. Her popularity with viewers resulted in Walters receiving more airtime, and in 1974 she became co-host of the program, the first woman to hold such a title on an American news program.<ref>{{cite book|last=Walters|first=Barbara|title=Audition: a memoir|year=2008|publisher=Knopf|location=NY|isbn=978-0-307-26646-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/205 205]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Walters|first=Barbara|title=Audition: a memoir|year=2008|publisher=Knopf|location=NY|isbn=978-0-307-26646-0|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Meaney, VP-TV News Programming|first=Donald|title=NBC-TV Press Release|date=April 22, 1974}}</ref> In 1976, she continued to be a pioneer for women in broadcasting by becoming the first female co-anchor of a network evening news program, alongside [[Harry Reasoner]] on the ''ABC Evening News''. From 1979 to 2004, Walters worked as a producer and co-host on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] newsmagazine ''20/20''. She also became known for an annual special aired on ABC, ''[[Barbara Walters' 10 Most Fascinating People]]''.\n\nWalters also created, produced, and co-hosted the ABC daytime talk show ''The View'', on which she appeared from 1997 until her retirement in 2014.<ref name=retirement>{{cite news |title=Walters to Announce 2014 Retirement on 'The View' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/13/business/media/barbara-walters-to-announce-2014-retirement-on-the-view.html?pagewanted=1&_r=2&hp& |accessdate=May 13, 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 13, 2013}}</ref> Thereafter, she continued to host a number of special reports for ''20/20'' as well as [[documentary]] series for [[Investigation Discovery]]. Her final on-air appearance for ABC News was in 2015.<ref name=\"adweek.com\">{{cite web |author=Chris Ariens |url=http://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/barbara-walters-return-to-2020-wins-the-hour-for-abc/260383 |title=Barbara Walters Return to 20/20 Wins the Hour for ABC &#124; TVNewser |publisher=Adweek.com |date=April 11, 2015 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"latimes1\">{{cite web |url=https://latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-barbara-walters-retirement-peter-rodger-interview-20140610-story.html |title=Barbara Walters returns from retirement for Peter Rodger interview |work=LA Times |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"abcnews.go.com\">{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Press_Release/barbara-walters-interviews-presidential-candidate-donald-trump-family/story?id=35261113 |title=Barbara Walters Interviews Presidential Candidate Donald Trump And His Family \u2013 ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=November 17, 2015 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"press.discovery.com\">{{cite web|url=https://press.discovery.com/us/id/programs/american-scandal-barbara-walters/|title=Barbara Walters Presents American Scandals : Programs : Investigation Discovery : Discovery Press Web|website=press.discovery.com}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/barbara-walters-reveals-annual-fascinating-people-list/story?id=35512361 |title=Barbara Walters Reveals Her Annual 'Most Fascinating People' List \u2013 ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=December 2, 2015 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Walters was ranked #34 on the ''[[TV Guide]]'' \"50 Greatest TV Stars of All Time\" list,<ref>{{cite journal |year=1996 |title=Special Collectors' Issue: 50 Greatest TV Stars of All Time |journal=[[TV Guide]] |issue=December 14\u201320 }}</ref> and in 2000 she received a Lifetime Achievement Award from the [[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]].\n\n==Early life==\nBarbara Walters was born in 1929{{#tag:ref|Sources confirming her birth year in 1929:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Barbara_Walters.aspx |title=Barbara Walters Facts, information, pictures &#124; Encyclopedia.com articles about Barbara Walters |publisher=Encyclopedia.com |date= |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author= |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/12/05/us/barbara-walters---fast-facts/ |title=Barbara Walters Fast Facts |publisher=CNN.com |date=September 29, 2015 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://openlibrary.org/subjects/person:barbara_walters_(1931-) |title=Barbara Walters (1931-) |publisher=Open Library |date= |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=TheBiography.us |url=http://thebiography.us/en/walters-barbara |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415211224/http://thebiography.us/en/walters-barbara |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 15, 2016 |title=Biography of Barbara Walters (1931-VVVV) |publisher=TheBiography.us |date=October 2, 1931 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebritorium.com/celebrity-birthday/Barbara-Walters-date-of-birth-1931-09-25-1273.htm|title=Barbara Walters Birthday - September 25, 1931 - List of Celebrities & their Date of Birth @ Celebritorium.com|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://biography.yourdictionary.com/barbara-walters |title=Barbara Walters Facts |publisher=Biography.yourdictionary.com |date= |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/people/1478076?c=people |title=Walters, Barbara (1931-) \u2013 People and organisations \u2013 Trove |publisher=Trove.nla.gov.au |date= |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.almanac.com/fact/barbara-walters-newscaster-born |title=When was Barbara Walters (newscaster) born? &#124; Old Farmer's Almanac |publisher=Almanac.com |date=September 25, 1931 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.torontopubliclibrary.ca/detail.jsp?Entt=RDM2402423&R=2402423 |title=Audition : a memoir : Walters, Barbara, 1931- : Book, Regular Print Book : Toronto Public Library |publisher=Torontopubliclibrary.ca |date=May 13, 2008 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/barbara-walters |title=Barbara Walters Interview &#124; Archive of American Television |publisher=Emmytvlegends.org |date= |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>|group=\"sources\"}} (although Walters herself has claimed 1931 in an on-camera interview)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7M7pYKYu8-w#t=138 |title=Barbara Walters Interview Part 1 of 4 \u2013 EMMYTVLEGENDS.ORG |publisher=YouTube |date=August 28, 2009 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref> in [[Boston]] to Dena (n\u00e9e Seletsky) and [[Lou Walters|Louis \"Lou\" Walters]] (born Louis Abraham Warmwater).<ref>{{cite book |last=Walters |first=Barbara |title=Audition: a memoir |year=2008 |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |location=New York |isbn=978-0-307-26646-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/9 9] |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W |url-access=registration }}</ref><ref>Stated on ''Finding Your Roots'', PBS, April 1, 2012</ref> Her parents were both Jewish,<ref name=\"Walters3\">{{cite news |last=Quinn |first=Sally |title=Television Personality Looks Anew At Religion |work=[[The Washington Post]]/[[Newsweek]] |date=December 22, 2006 |url=http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/guestvoices/2006/12/television_personality_looks_a.html |accessdate=December 22, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070106163807/http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/guestvoices/2006/12/television_personality_looks_a.html |archivedate=January 6, 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> and descendants of refugees from the former [[Russian Empire]].<ref name=\"Audition\">{{cite book |title=Audition: A Memoir |last=Walters |first=Barbara |year=2008 |publisher=[[Alfred A. Knopf]] |location=New York |isbn=978-0-307-26646-0 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/7 7]\u201313 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W |url-access=registration }}</ref> Walters's paternal grandfather, Abraham Isaac Warmwater, was born in [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]], Poland, and emigrated to the United Kingdom, changing his name to Abraham Walters (the original family surname was Waremwasser).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/03/23/149222907/helping-celebrities-find-their-roots|title=Helping Celebrities Find Their Roots|publisher=}}</ref> Walters's father, Lou, was born in London c. 1896 and moved to New York with his father and two brothers, arriving August 28, 1909. His mother and four sisters arrived in 1910.<ref>{{cite book |last=Walters |first=Barbara |title=Audition: a memoir |year=2008 |publisher=Knopf |location=NY |isbn=978-0-307-26646-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/10 10] |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W |url-access=registration }}</ref> During her childhood her father managed the [[Latin Quarter (nightclub)|Latin Quarter]] nightclub. This club was owned in partnership with E.M. Loew and initially located in Boston, Massachusetts. In 1949, her father opened the New York version of the Latin Quarter. He also worked as a Broadway producer where he produced the ''[[Ziegfeld Follies]] of 1943''.<ref name=\"Walters2\">{{cite news |title=Lou Walters, Nightclub Impresario and Founder of Latin Quarter, Dies |page=36 |website=The New York Times |date=August 16, 1977}}</ref><ref>{{IBDB name|id=7381|name=Lou Walters}}</ref> He also was the Entertainment Director for the [[Tropicana Resort and Casino]] in Las Vegas, Nevada, where he imported the \"Folies Berg\u00e8re\" stage show from Paris to the resort's main showroom.<ref>[http://www.a2zlasvegas.com/hotels/history/h-trop.html Tropicana \u2013 Las Vegas Strip]. A2zlasvegas.com. Retrieved on October 27, 2011.</ref> Walters's brother, Burton, died in 1944 of [[pneumonia]].<ref name=\"Conaway\">James Conaway, \"How to talk with Barbara Walters about practically anything,\" ''The New York Times'', September 10, 1972, page SM40, 43\u201344</ref> Walters's elder sister, Jacqueline, was born [[mentally disabled]]<ref name=\"actors\">Stated in interview at ''[[Inside the Actors Studio]]''</ref> and died of [[ovarian cancer]] in 1985.\n\nAccording to Walters, her father made and lost several fortunes throughout his life in show business. He was a booking agent, and unlike her uncles who were in the shoe and dress business, his job was not very safe. During the good times, Walters recalls her father taking her to the rehearsals of the night club shows he directed and produced. The actresses and dancers would make a huge fuss over her and twirl her around until she was dizzy. Then she said her father would take her out for hot dogs, their favorite.<ref name=\"Walters, Barbara 2008\">Walters, Barbara (2008). ''Audition: A Memoir''. New York: Alfred A. Knopf</ref>\n\nAccording to Walters, being surrounded by celebrities when she was young kept her from being \"in awe\" of them.<ref name=\"actors\" /> When she was a young woman, Walters's father lost his night clubs and the family's [[Penthouse apartment|penthouse]] on [[Central Park West]]. As Walters recalled, \"He had a [[Mental breakdown|breakdown]]. He went down to live in our house in Florida, and then the government took the house, and they took the car, and they took the furniture.\" Of her mother, she said, \"My mother should have married the way her friends did, to a man who was a doctor or who was in the dress business.\"<ref name=\"Bumiller\">Elisabeth Bumiller, \"So Famous, Such Clout, She Could Interview Herself\", ''The New York Times'', April 21, 1996, page H1</ref>\n\nWalters attended Lawrence School, a public school in Brookline, Massachusetts, to the middle of fifth grade, when her father moved the family to Miami Beach in 1939, where she also attended public school. After her father moved the family to New York City, she went to eighth grade at [[Ethical Culture Fieldston School]], after which the family moved back to Miami Beach. Then, she went back to New York City, where she attended [[Birch Wathen Lenox|Birch Wathen School]]<ref name=\"New York Magazine\">[https://nymag.com/news/features/28519/index1.html \"Can Barbara Walters's Career Survive Rosie and Donald's War?\"] ''New York'' (March 5, 2007). Retrieved on October 27, 2011.</ref><ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/25/books/and-now-back-to-you-barbara.html |work=The New York Times |title=And Now Back to You, Barbara |first=Maureen |last=Dowd |date=March 25, 1990 |accessdate=April 26, 2010}}</ref> from which she graduated in 1947. In 1951 she received a B.A. in English from [[Sarah Lawrence College]]<ref name=\"biography.com\">{{cite web |title=Barbara Walters Biography |publisher=biography.com |url=http://www.biography.com/people/barbara-walters-9523127}}</ref> and immediately looked for work in New York City. After about a year at a small advertising agency, she began working at the NBC network affiliate in New York City, WNBT-TV (now [[WNBC]]), doing publicity and writing press releases. She began producing a 15-minute children's program, ''Ask the Camera'', directed by [[Roone Arledge]] in 1953. She began producing for TV host [[Igor Cassini]]/[[Cholly Knickerbocker]]. However, she left the network after her boss pressured her to marry him and engaged in a fist-fight with a man she preferred to date. Then she went to WPIX to produce the ''Eloise McElhone Show''; it was canceled in 1954. She became a writer on ''The Morning Show'' at [[CBS]] in 1955.\n\n==Career==\n\n===''The Today Show''===\n[[File:Today show panel 1973.JPG|thumb|[[Gene Shalit]], Barbara Walters, and [[Frank McGee (journalist)|Frank McGee]] in ''The Today Show'', 1973.]]\nAfter a few years as a publicist with [[Tex McCrary]] Inc. and a job as a writer at [[Redbook]] magazine, Walters joined [[NBC]]'s ''[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]]'' as a writer and researcher in 1961.<ref name=\"actors\" /> She moved up to become that show's regular \"Today Girl,\" handling lighter assignments and the weather. In her autobiography, she describes this era before the [[Feminism|Women's Movement]] as a time when it was believed that nobody would take a woman seriously reporting \"hard news.\" Previous [[Today (NBC program)#Today Girls|\"Today Girls\"]] (whom Walters called \"tea pourers\") included [[Florence Henderson]], [[Helen O'Connell]], [[Estelle Parsons]] and [[Lee Meriwether]].<ref>''Audition'', pp. 107\u2013114</ref> Within a year, she had become a reporter-at-large developing, writing, and editing her own reports and interviews. One very well received film segment was \"A Day in the Life of a Novice Nun,\" edited by then-first assistant film editor Donald Swerdlow (now Don Canaan), who was subsequently promoted to become a full film editor at NBC News.<ref name=\"actors\" /> She had a great relationship with host Hugh Downs for years. When [[Frank McGee (journalism)|Frank McGee]] was named host, he refused to do joint interviews with Walters unless he was given the first three questions. She was not named co-host of the show until McGee's death in 1974 when NBC officially designated Walters as the program's first female co-host. Beginning in 1971, she also hosted her own local NBC affiliate show, ''[[Not for Women Only]],'' which ran in the mornings after ''The Today Show.''<ref name=\"thompson\">{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Kathleen |title=Barbara Walters |url=https://jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/walters-barbara |website=Jewish Women's Archive |publisher=Jewish Women's Archive |accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>''Audition'', p. 190</ref>\n\n[[File:Barbara Walters \u00a9Lynn Gilbert.gif|thumb|Barbara Walters in her office, as photographed by [[Lynn Gilbert]] in 1979.]]\n\n===''ABC Evening News'' and ''20/20''===\nWalters has seldom minced words when describing the visible, on-the-air disdain her co-anchor [[Harry Reasoner]] displayed for her when she was teamed up with him on the ''[[ABC Evening News]]'' from 1976\u201378. Reasoner had a difficult relationship with Walters, because he disliked having a co-anchor, even though he worked with former CBS colleague [[Howard K. Smith]] nightly on ABC for several years. In 1981, five years after the start of their short-lived ABC partnership and well after Reasoner returned to CBS News, Walters and her former co-anchor had a memorable (and cordial) ''20/20'' interview on the occasion of Reasoner's new book release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.today.com/popculture/barbara-walters-legendary-career-offers-view-back-today-2D79669608|title=Barbara Walters' legendary career offers a 'View' back to TODAY|website=TODAY.com|language=en|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWalters is also known for her years on the ABC newsmagazine ''20/20'' where she reunited with former ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today Show]]'' host [[Hugh Downs]] in 1979.<ref name=\"actors\" /> Throughout her career at ABC, Walters has appeared on ABC news specials as a commentator, including presidential inaugurations and the coverage of [[9/11]]. She was also chosen to be the moderator for the third and final debate between candidates [[Jimmy Carter]] and [[Gerald Ford]], held on the campus of the College of William and Mary at [[Phi Beta Kappa Memorial Hall]] in [[Williamsburg, Virginia]], during the [[1976 United States presidential election|1976 presidential election]].<ref name=CNN>[https://web.archive.org/web/20001006083517/http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2000/debates/history.story/1976.html CNN: 1976 Presidential Debates]. Retrieved on June 14, 2008.</ref> In 1984, she moderated a Presidential debate held at the Dana Center for the Humanities at [[Saint Anselm College]] in [[Goffstown, New Hampshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VkIsAAAAIBAJ&pg=3623,1412416&dq=barbara%20walters%20saint%20anselm&hl=en|title=Herald-Journal - Google News Archive Search|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n====Interviews====\n[[File:Barbara Walters-The Fords.jpg|right|thumb|Walters interviewing President [[Gerald Ford]] and [[Betty Ford]] in 1976.]]\n\nWalters is known for \"personality journalism\" and her \"scoop\" interviews.<ref name=\"actors\" /> In November 1977, she achieved a joint interview with Egypt's President, [[Anwar Al Sadat]], and Israel's Prime Minister, [[Menachem Begin]]. According to ''The New York Times'', when she went mano a mano with Walter Cronkite to interview both world leaders, at the end of Cronkite's interview, he is clearly heard saying: \"Did Barbara get anything I didn't get?\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Maselin|first= J. |date=May 5, 2008|title=Hard sell, soft touch, and the right question|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/05/books/05masl.html?_r=1&}}</ref> Her interviews with world leaders from all walks of life are a chronicle of the latter part of the 20th century.<ref name=\"actors\" /> They include the [[Pahlavi dynasty|Shah of Iran]], [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]], and his wife, the Empress [[Farah Pahlavi]]; Russia's [[Boris Yeltsin]] and [[Vladimir Putin]]; China's [[Jiang Zemin]]; the UK's [[Margaret Thatcher]]; Cuba's [[Fidel Castro]], as well as India's [[Indira Gandhi]], Czechoslovakia's [[V\u00e1clav Havel]], Libya's [[Muammar al-Gaddafi]], King [[Hussein of Jordan]], King [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia]], and Venezuelan President [[Hugo Chavez]], among many others. Other interviews with influential people include pop icon [[Michael Jackson]], actress [[Katharine Hepburn]], ''Vogue'' editor [[Anna Wintour]], and in 1980 [[Laurence Olivier|Sir Laurence Olivier]]. Walters considered [[Robert Smithdas]], a deaf-blind man who spent his life improving the lives of other individuals who are deaf-blind, as her most inspirational interview.\n\nWalters was widely lampooned for asking actress [[Katharine Hepburn]], \"If you were a tree, what kind would you be?\" On her last 20/20 television episode, Walters showed video of the Hepburn interview, showing the actress saying that she would like to be a tree. Walters merely followed up with the question, \"What kind of a tree?\",<ref name=\"actors\" /><ref>[http://katethegreatnet.proboards.com/index.cgi?board=tv&action=display&thread=1133561741 Kate the Great, The Katharine Hepburn Forum \u2013 The Barbara Walters Interview] Retrieved May 10, 2008{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2008|accessdate=May 8, 2008}}</ref> and Hepburn responded \"an oak\" because they are strong and pretty. According to Walters, for years Hepburn refused her requests for an interview. And when she finally agreed to one, she said she wanted to meet her first. Walters walked in all smiles and ready to please, while Hepburn was at the top of the stairs and barked, \"You're late. Have you brought me chocolates?\" Walters hadn't but said she never showed up without them from then on. They had several other meetings since that first time, mostly in Hepburn's living room where she would give Walters her opinions. Careers and marriage did not mix. Children and careers were out of the question. Walters said Hepburn's opinions stuck with her so much, she could repeat them almost verbatim to this day.<ref name=\"Walters, Barbara 2008\" />\n\nHer television special about Cuban leader [[Fidel Castro]] aired on ABC-TV on June 9, 1977. Although the footage of her two days of interviewing Castro in Cuba showed his personality, in part, as freewheeling, charming, and humorous,<ref>{{cite book |last=Walters |first=Barbara |title=Audition: a memoir |year=2008 |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |location=New York |isbn=978-0-307-26646-0 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/324 324]\u2013333 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W |url-access=registration }}</ref> she pointedly said to him, \"You allow no dissent. Your newspapers, radio, television, motions picture are under state control.\" To this, he replied, \"Barbara, our concept of freedom of the press is not yours. If you asked us if a newspaper could appear here against socialism, I can say honestly no, it cannot appear. It would not be allowed by the party, the government, or the people. In that sense we do not have the freedom of the press that you possess in the U.S. And we are very satisfied about that.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Walters |first=Barbara |title=Audition: a memoir |year=2008 |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |location=New York |isbn=978-0-307-26646-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/327 327] |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W |url-access=registration }}</ref> She concluded the broadcast of the interview by remarking, \"What we disagreed on most profoundly is the meaning of freedom\u2014and that is what truly separates us.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Walters |first=Barbara |title=Audition: a memoir |year=2008 |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |location=New York |isbn=978-0-307-26646-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W/page/329 329] |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_B004FR2X2W |url-access=registration }}</ref> At the time, Walters kept quiet about seeing New York Yankees owner [[George Steinbrenner]], pitcher [[Whitey Ford]], and several coaches in Cuba, there to assist Cuban ballplayers.\n\nOn March 3, 1999, her interview of [[Monica Lewinsky]] was seen by a record 74 million viewers, the highest rating ever for a news program.<ref>{{cite web |last=de Moraes |first=Lisa |title=Monica Lewinsky Beats the Competition |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/tv030599.htm |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=May 12, 2013 |date=March 5, 1999}}</ref> Walters asked Lewinsky, \"What will you tell your children when you have them?\" Lewinsky replied, \"Mommy made a big mistake,\" at which point Walters brought the program to a dramatic conclusion, turning to the viewers and saying, \"And that is the understatement of the year.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Shales |first=Tom |title=Once More, With Feeling |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/shales030499.htm |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=May 12, 2013 |date=March 4, 1999}}</ref>\n\n===''The View''===\n[[File:Barack Obama guests on The View.jpg|thumb|right|''The View's'' panel (left\u2013right [[Whoopi Goldberg]], Barbara Walters, [[Joy Behar]], [[Sherri Shepherd]] and [[Elisabeth Hasselbeck]]) interview [[United States President]] [[Barack Obama]] on July 29, 2010.]]\n{{Main|The View (talk show)}}\n\nWalters was a co-host of the daytime talk show ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]],'' of which she also is co-creator and co-executive producer with her business partner, [[Bill Geddie]]. It premiered on August 11, 1997.<ref name=\"actors\" />\n\nWalters described the show in its original opening credits as a forum for women of \"different generations, backgrounds, and views.\" She added, \"Be careful what you wish for...\" on the opening credits of its second season. Through ''The View'', she was able to clinch two [[Daytime Emmy Award]]s for Best Talk Show in 2003 and Best Talk Show Host (with longtime host [[Joy Behar]], moderator [[Whoopi Goldberg]], [[Elisabeth Hasselbeck]], and [[Sherri Shepherd]]) in 2009.\n\nWalters retired from being a co-host on May 15, 2014. Although retired, Walters returned as a guest co-host on an intermittent basis throughout 2014 and 2015.\n\n===Retirement===\nSince leaving her role as ''20/20'' co-host in 2004, Walters remained as a part-time contributor of special programming and interviews for [[ABC News]] until 2016.\n\nOn March 7, 2010, Barbara Walters announced she would no longer hold Oscar interviews, but will still be working with ABC and on ''The View.''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/oscars/7393741/Barbara-Walters-to-host-last-Oscars-special-amid-overexposure-of-stars.html |title=Barbara Walters to host last Oscars special amid 'overexposure' of stars |accessdate=March 8, 2010 |last=Allen |first=Nick |date=March 7, 2010 |work=Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited 2010 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn a November 2010 episode of ''The View'', while interviewing [[Larry King]] on his retirement from CNN, Walters alluded to her impending retirement, stating, \"I know when my time's coming.\"\n\nOn March 28, 2013, numerous media outlets reported that Barbara Walters would retire in May 2014 and that she would make the announcement on the show four days later.<ref name=\"NYT Carter Walter nearing retirement\">{{cite news |last=Carter |first=Bill |title=Barbara Walters Said to Be Nearing Retirement |url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/28/barbara-walters-said-to-be-nearing-retirement/ |accessdate=April 17, 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=March 28, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"WP Walters to announce retiring\">{{cite news |last=de Moraes |first=Lisa |title=Barbara Walters to announce she's retiring \u2014 next year |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/tv-column/post/barbara-walters-to-announce-shes-retiring--next-year/2013/03/28/c6d7d296-97f4-11e2-b68f-dc5c4b47e519_blog.html |accessdate=April 17, 2013 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=March 28, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Baltimore Sun Walter retiring\">{{cite news |last=Zurawik |first=David |title=Barbara Walters retiring after 52 years in television |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-03-28/entertainment/bal-barbara-walters-retiring-after-52-years-in-television-20130328_1_co-anchor-barbara-walters-harry-reasoner |accessdate=April 17, 2013 |newspaper=The Baltimiore Sun |date=March 28, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"MSNBC Walters trailblazer\">{{cite news |last=Whitaker |first=Morgan |title=Barbara Walters, TV trailblazer, set to retire |url=http://tv.msnbc.com/2013/03/30/barbara-walters-tv-trailblazer-set-to-retire/ |accessdate=April 17, 2013 |newspaper=MSNBC |date=March 30, 2013}}</ref> However, on the April 1 episode, Walters neither confirmed nor denied the retirement rumors; she said \"if and when I might have an announcement to make, I will do it on this program, I promise, and the paparazzi guys -- you will be the last to know\".<ref name=\"Newsday Walters no denial\">{{cite news |last=Gay |first=Verne |title=Barbara Walters on retirement: No comment, but no denial either |url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/tv-zone-1.811968/barbara-walters-on-retirement-no-comment-but-no-denial-either-1.4983373 |accessdate=April 17, 2013 |newspaper=Newsday |date=April 1, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"LA Times Walters no retirement\">{{cite news |last=Day |first=Patrick Kevin |title='The View's' Barbara Walters has no retirement announcement yet |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-the-views-barbara-walters-has-no-retirement-announcement-yet-20130401,0,5460912.story |accessdate=April 17, 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=April 1, 2013}}</ref> Walters confirmed six weeks later that she would be retiring from television hosting and interviewing in May 2014, as originally reported; she made the official announcement on the May 13, 2013, episode of ''The View'' while also announcing that she will continue as the show's executive producer for as long as it's on the air.<ref name=\"NYT Walters to Announce\">{{cite news |last=Carter |first=Bill |title=Walters to Announce 2014 Retirement on 'The View' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/13/business/media/barbara-walters-to-announce-2014-retirement-on-the-view.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 |accessdate=May 13, 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Chicago Tribune BW to announce\">{{cite news |title=Barbara Walters to announce retirement on \"The View,\" says ABC |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/sns-rt-us-barbarawaltersbre94c02u-20130512,0,3784948.story |accessdate=May 13, 2013 |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=May 12, 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"USA Today BW retirement\">{{cite news |last=Schwartz |first=Bruce |title=Barbara Walters will announce retirement |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2013/05/12/barbara-walters-will-announce-retirement/2154541/ |accessdate=May 13, 2013 |newspaper=USA Today |date=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN BW to retire\">{{cite news |last=Ford |first=Dana |title=Barbara Walters to retire next year |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/05/12/showbiz/barbara-walters-retirement/?hpt=hp_t2 |accessdate=May 13, 2013 |newspaper=CNN |date=May 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"LA Times Groundbreaking\">{{cite news |last=Villarreal |first=Yvonne |title=Groundbreaking TV journalist Barbara Walters is set to retire |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-groundbreaking-tv-journalist-barbara-walters-set-to-hang-it-up-20130512,0,4654559.story |accessdate=May 13, 2013 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=May 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 10, 2014, it was announced that she would be 'coming out of retirement' in order to do a special 20/20 interview with [[Peter Rodger]], the father of Elliot Rodger who had committed the [[2014 Isla Vista killings]].<ref name=\"latimes1\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://jewishbusinessnews.com/2014/06/11/barbara-walters-is-already-set-to-interview-again-less-than-one-month-after-formally-retiring/ |title=Barbara Walters is Already Set to Interview Again Less Than One Month After Formally Retiring \u2013 Jewish Business News |publisher=Jewishbusinessnews.com |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSince then, she has hosted special ''20/20'' episodes featuring interviews with [[Mary Kay Letourneau]]<ref name=\"adweek.com\" /> and [[Donald Trump|Donald]] and [[Melania Trump]].<ref name=\"abcnews.go.com\" />\n\nIn 2015, Walters hosted the documentary series ''American Scandals'' on [[Investigation Discovery]].<ref name=\"press.discovery.com\" />\n\nWalters continued to host her [[Barbara Walters' 10 Most Fascinating People|10 Most Fascinating People]] series in 2014<ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2014/10/barbara-walters-presents-the-10-most-fascinating-people-of-2014-returns-to-abc-primetime-december-14-9-11-pm-et/ |title=\"BARBARA WALTERS PRESENTS: THE 10 MOST FASCINATING PEOPLE OF 2014,\" RETURNS TO ABC PRIMETIME DECEMBER 14, 9-11 PM ET \u2013 ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=October 21, 2014 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref> and 2015.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\nHer final on-air interview was of presidential candidate Donald Trump for ABC News in December 2015.<ref>{{cite web |author=Lisa de Moraes |url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/donald-trump-barbara-walters-not-bigot-muslim-ban-plan-video-1201660700/ |title=[VIDEO&#93; Donald Trump Tells Barbara Walters \"I'm Not A Bigot,\" Clearing That Up |publisher=Deadline |date=December 8, 2015 |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWalters last appeared publicly in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barbara's Secret Struggle! 'Gravely' Ill Walters Not Seen In Public For 130 Days|url= https://www.radaronline.com/exclusives/2016/11/barbara-walters-dying-fears-the-view/|publisher=radaronline.com|accessdate=February 9, 2019|date= November 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=closer>{{Cite web|url=https://www.closerweekly.com/posts/where-is-barbara-walters-142633/|title=Where is Barbara Walters?|first=Samantha|last=Fagarelli|work=[[Closer (magazine)|closer]]|date=October 19, 2019|access-date=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWalters has been married four times to three different men. Her first husband was Robert Henry Katz, a business executive and former Navy lieutenant. They married on June 20, 1955, at [[Plaza Hotel|The Plaza Hotel]] in New York City.<ref name=\"Walters1\" /><ref>\"Katz\u2014Walters\", ''The New York Times'', June 21, 1955, page 36</ref> The marriage was reportedly annulled after 11 months,<ref>{{cite news |title=Top-Drawer Life of Barbara Walters |newspaper=Beaver County Times |location=Pennsylvania |date=October 7, 1974 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2002&dat=19741007&id=qvsqAAAAIBAJ&pg=886,1378488}}</ref> or in 1957.<ref>{{cite news |title=Walter's fiance is a man of few words, big bucks |newspaper=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=June 18, 1985 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB7C18EDD9D9D82&p_field_direct-0=document_id}}</ref>\n\nHer second husband was [[Lee Guber]], theatrical producer and theater owner. They married on December 8, 1963, and divorced in 1976. They have one daughter, Jacqueline Dena Guber (born 1968, adopted the same year).\n\nHer third husband was Merv Adelson, the CEO of [[Lorimar]] Television. They married in 1981 and divorced in 1984. They remarried in 1986 and divorced for the second time in 1992.\n\nShe dated lawyer<ref name=miller>{{cite book|last=Miller |first=Neil |title=Out of the Past: Gay and Lesbian History from 1869 to the Present |publisher=Advocate Books |year=2005 |pages=Ch. 18 |url=http://www2.english.uiuc.edu/finnegan/English%20256/Miller.htm |isbn=1-55583-870-7 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090902224218/http://www2.english.uiuc.edu/finnegan/English%20256/Miller.htm |archivedate=September 2, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wolfe |first=Tom |authorlink=Tom Wolfe |title=Dangerous Obsessions |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 3, 1988 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/04/03/books/dangerous-obsessions.html?pagewanted=print}}</ref> [[Roy Cohn]] in college; he said that he proposed marriage to Walters the night before her wedding to Lee Guber, but Walters denied this.<ref name=\"Conaway\" /> She explained her lifelong devotion to Cohn as gratitude for his help in her adoption of her daughter, Jacqueline.<ref name=\"Oppenheimer\">{{citation |author=Jerry Oppenheimer |title=Barbara Walters: An Unauthorized Biography |publisher=St. Martin's Press |year=1990}}</ref> In her autobiography, Walters says she also felt grateful to Cohn because of his legal assistance to her father. According to Walters, her father was the subject of an arrest warrant for \"failure to appear\" after he failed to show up for a New York court date because the family was in Las Vegas, and Cohn was able to have the charge dismissed.<ref name=\"Wiegand\">{{Cite news |last=Wiegand |first=David |title=Barbara Walters gets personal. This time, she's candid about her own life. |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |date=May 5, 2008 |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/05/05/DDTU10H1P9.DTL}}</ref> Walters testified as a character witness at Cohn's 1986 disbarment trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2017/06/donald-trump-roy-cohn-relationship|title=How Donald Trump and Roy Cohn's Ruthless Symbiosis Changed America|first=Marie|last=Brenner|publisher=|accessdate=August 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWalters dated future U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman [[Alan Greenspan]] in the 1970s<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/09232007/business/listen_to_shiller__not_the_tv_.htm |title=LISTEN TO SHILLER, NOT THE TV SHILLS |author=Terry Keenan |work=New York Post |date=September 23, 2007 |accessdate=October 13, 2007}}</ref> and was linked romantically to United States Senator [[John Warner]] in the\n1990s.\n\nIn Walters's autobiography ''Audition'', she claimed that she had an affair in the 1970s with [[Edward Brooke]], then a married [[United States Senate|United States Senator]] from Massachusetts. It is not clear whether Walters also was married at the time. Walters said they ended the affair to protect their careers from scandal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barbara Walters: I had affair with U.S. senator |url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/books/05/01/tv.walters.affair.ap/index.html|url-status=dead |work=CNN |agency=Associated Press (AP) |date=May 1, 2008| archivedate=May 2, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502133009/http://www.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/books/05/01/tv.walters.affair.ap/index.html}}</ref> In 2007 she dated [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning gerontologist [[Robert Neil Butler]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secondact.com/2010/07/friends-of-robert-butler-describe/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105073845/http://www.secondact.com/2010/07/friends-of-robert-butler-describe/|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 5, 2011|title=The Father of Geriatrics Acted Anything But Old - Ageism - SecondAct.com|date=January 5, 2011|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWalters is close friends with [[Tom Brokaw]] and [[Woody Allen]], and was close friends with [[Joan Rivers]] as well with former [[Fox News]] head [[Roger Ailes]] from the late 1960s until his death in 2017.<ref>Fehrman, Craig (January 21, 2011) [http://www.salon.com/news/politics/war_room/2011/01/21/roger_ailes_fehrman/index.html When Roger Ailes was honest about what he does] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228232838/http://www.salon.com/news/politics/war_room/2011/01/21/roger_ailes_fehrman/index.html |date=February 28, 2011 }}, ''[[Salon.com]]''</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Walters appeared on CNN's ''[[Piers Morgan Live]]'' and revealed that not having more children is her greatest regret in life.<ref>{{YouTube|TwBFDnN97D0}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Barbara Walters: \"I Regret Not Having More Children\" |date=December 18, 2013 |website=The Huffington Post |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/12/18/barbara-walters-regret-children_n_4467162.html}}</ref>\n\n===Health===\nWalters announced on the May 10, 2010, episode of ''The View'' that she would be undergoing [[open heart surgery]] to replace a faulty [[aortic valve]]. She added that she knew for quite a while that she was suffering from [[aortic valve stenosis]], even though she was symptom-free. The procedure to fix the faulty heart valve \"went well, and the doctors are very pleased with the outcome,\" Walters's spokeswoman, Cindi Berger, said in a statement on May 14, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2010/05/14/barbara_walters_heart_valve_surgery_went_well/ |title=Barbara Walters' heart valve surgery 'went well' |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=May 14, 2010 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=April 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn July 9, 2010, it was announced that Walters would return to ''The View'' and her [[Sirius XM]] satellite show, ''Here's Barbara'', in September 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radio-info.com/news/making-moves-thursday-july-8-2010 |title=Making Moves: Thursday, July 8, 2010 |date=July 8, 2010 |work=Radio-Info.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714170331/http://www.radio-info.com/news/making-moves-thursday-july-8-2010 |archivedate=July 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/Barbara-Walters-Returns-to-prnews-1477182584.html?x=0&.v=1 |title=Barbara Walters Returns to Media Hosting Her Weekly SIRIUS XM Radio Show on July 12 |work=[[Yahoo! Finance]]}}{{Dead link|date=September 2012}}</ref>\n\nFour years later, Walters retired permanently from both shows.<ref>{{cite web|title='The View' co-hosts through the years: Barbara Walters, Whoopi Goldberg and more|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/the-view-hosts-1.8695392|publisher=newsday.com|accessdate=February 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nBarbara Walters was inducted into the [[Television Hall of Fame]] in 1989. On June 15, 2007, Walters received a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]. She has won Daytime and Prime Time Emmy Awards, a [[Women in Film Crystal + Lucy Awards|Women in Film Lucy Award]], and a [[GLAAD]] Excellence in Media award. Her impact on popular culture is illustrated by [[Gilda Radner]]'s \"Baba Wawa\" impersonation of her on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'',<ref name=\"actors\" /> featuring her idiosyncratic speech with its [[Rhotacism (speech impediment)|rounded \"R\"]]. Her name also appeared in the January 23, 1995 ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' Monday [[Crossword|Crossword Puzzle]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/crosswords/game/daily/1995/01/23|title=The Crossword|last=Robbins|first=Sidney L.|date=January 23, 1995|editor-last=Shortz|editor-first=Will|website=New York Times|url-status=live|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In 2008, she was honored with the [[Disney Legends]] award, given to those who made an outstanding contribution to [[The Walt Disney Company]], which owns the network [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]. That same year, she received the Lifetime Achievement Award from the [[New York Women's Agenda]]. On September 21, 2009, Walters was honored with a Lifetime Achievement Award at the 30th Annual News and Documentary Emmy Awards at New York City's Lincoln Center.\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{more citations needed|section|date=September 2017}}<!--Emmys and NAACP Image Awards are not cited-->\n* 1985: [[Paul White (journalist)|Paul White]] Award, [[Radio Television Digital News Association]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rtdna.org/content/paul_white_award#.U4FBHS8-Ngc |title=Paul White Award |publisher=[[Radio Television Digital News Association]] |accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n[[Daytime Emmy Awards]]\n* '''1975 Award for Daytime Emmy for Outstanding Talk Show Host (''Today'')'''\n* 1998 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 1998 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 1999 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 1999 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 2000 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 2000 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 2001 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 2001 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 2002 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 2002 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* '''2003 Award for Best Talk Show (''The View'')'''\n* 2003 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 2006 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 2006 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 2007 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 2007 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* 2008 Nomination for Best Talk Show (''The View'')\n* 2008 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n* '''2009 Award for Daytime Emmy for Outstanding Talk Show Host (''The View'')''' (with Whoopi Goldberg, Joy Behar, Elisabeth Hasselbeck and Sherri Shepherd)\n* 2010 Nomination for Best Talk Show Host (''The View'')\n\n[[NAACP Image Award]]\n* '''2009 Award for Best Talk Series (''The View'')'''\n* 2010 Nomination for Best Talk Series\n\n[[Women in Film Los Angeles|Women in Film]] [[Women in Film Crystal + Lucy Awards|Crystal + Lucy Award]]\n* 1998 [[Women in Film Crystal + Lucy Awards#THE LUCY AWARD|Lucy Award]] in recognition of her excellence and innovation in her creative works that have enhanced the perception of women through the medium of television.<ref>[http://wif.org/past-recipients Past Recipients] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724120329/http://www.wif.org/past-recipients |date=July 24, 2011 }}. Wif.org. Retrieved on October 27, 2011.</ref>\n\n==Books==\nIn the late 1960s, Walters wrote a magazine article, \"How to Talk to Practically Anyone About Practically Anything\", which drew upon the kinds of things people said to her, which were often mistakes.<ref name=\"Memoir186-189\">''Audition: A Memoir'', pp. 186\u20139</ref> Shortly after the article appeared, she received a letter from [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] expressing interest in expanding it into a book. Walters felt that it would help \"tongue-tied, socially awkward people\u2014the many people who worry that they can't think of the right thing to say to start a conversation.\"<ref name=\"Memoir186-189\" /> She published the book ''How to Talk with Practically Anybody about Practically Anything'' in 1970, with the assistance of [[ghostwriter]] [[June Callwood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.cbc.ca/arts_entertainment/media/topics/1393-8719/ |title=June Callwood interview by Patrick Watson |date=September 21, 1979 |accessdate=October 18, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521164734/http://archives.cbc.ca/arts_entertainment/media/topics/1393-8719/ |archivedate=May 21, 2011 }}</ref> To Walters's great surprise, the book was a success. As of 2008, it had gone through eight printings, sold hundreds of thousands of copies worldwide, and had been translated into at least six languages.<ref name=\"Memoir186-189\" />\n\nShe published her autobiography, ''[[Audition: A Memoir]]'', in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/05/books/05masl.html |title='Audition: A Memoir' by Barbara Walters |first=Janet |last=Maslin |date=May 5, 2008 |accessdate=December 17, 2016 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Barbara Walters' 10 Most Fascinating People]]\n* [[New Yorkers in journalism]]\n\n== Notes ==\n=== Explanatory notes ===\n{{reflist|group=sources}}\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite book |title=Seen and Heard: The Women of Television News |first=Nichola D. |last=Gutgold |publisher=Lexington Books |year=2008}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|910181|Barbara Walters}}\n* [https://abcnews.go.com/search?searchtext=time%20tunnel&from=0&to=9&type=video ABC News' \"Time Tunnel\" page containing clips of numerous newscasts on which Walters appeared]\n* [https://www.amazon.com/dp/B002KAOS24 Excerpts from 2008 autobiography, ''Audition: A Memoir'']\n* [http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/barbara-walters Barbara Walters Archive of American Television Interview]\n* [http://www.makers.com/barbara-walters Barbara Walters] Video produced by ''[[Makers: Women Who Make America]]''\n\n{{ABC News Personalities}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Barbara Walters\n|list =\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Lifetime Achievement}}\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Talk Show Host}}\n{{TCA Career Achievement Award}}\n{{1989 Television Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n\n{{portal bar|Biography|Journalism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walters, Barbara}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:ABC News personalities]]\n[[Category:American memoirists]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American television news anchors]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:American women television journalists]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Talk Show Host winners]]\n[[Category:Ethical Culture Fieldston School alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American journalists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish women writers]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Miami Beach Senior High School alumni]]\n[[Category:NBC News people]]\n[[Category:People from Brookline, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People with dementia]]\n[[Category:Sarah Lawrence College alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Boston]]\n[[Category:Writers from Miami]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Women memoirists]]\n[[Category:Women television writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Birch Wathen Lenox School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:mentally disabled\u2192Disabilities affecting intellectual abilities", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barbara_Walters"}
{"title_page": "Ludwig Drums", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Ludwig Drums\n| logo = Ludwig Drums logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| image_alt =\n| image_caption =\n| trading_name =\n| native_name =\n| native_name_lang =    <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{lang|[code]|[name]}}. -->\n| romanized_name =\n| former_name =\n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| traded_as =\n| ISIN =\n| industry = [[Musical instrument]]s\n| genre =               <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate =\n| predecessor =         <!-- or: | predecessors = -->\n| successor =           <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1909}} in [[Chicago]] <ref name=hist/>\n| founder = [[William F. Ludwig, Sr.|William F.]] & Theobald Ludwig <ref name=hist/>\n| defunct =  <!-- {{end date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city = [[North Carolina]]\n| location_country = [[United States]]\n| coordinates =\n| locations =  <!-- Number of locations -->\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people =\n| products = [[Drum kit]]s and [[drum hardware|hardware]], [[marimba]]s, [[vibraphone]]s, [[xylophone]]s, [[mark tree|bar chimes]]\n| brands =\n| production =\n| services =\n| revenue =\n| operating_income =\n| net_income =\n| aum = <!-- Only for financial-service companies -->\n| assets =\n| equity =\n| owner =  <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| members =\n| num_employees =\n| parent = [[Conn-Selmer]]\n| divisions =\n| subsid =\n| website = [https://www.ludwig-drums.com/ ludwig-drums.com]\n| footnotes =\n| intl =  <!-- \"true\" or \"yes\" if company is international, otherwise omit -->\n| bodystyle =\n}}\n[[File:Ludwig Drums 2020 by Glenn Francis.jpg|right|thumb|Ludwig Drums Exhibit at 'The NAMM Show' on January 17, 2020 in Anaheim, California]] \n'''Ludwig Drums''' is a [[United States|US]] [[musical instrument]]s [[manufacturing company|manufacturer]]s, focused on [[percussion instruments|percussion]]. The brand achieved significant popularity in the 1960s due to the endorsement of [[the Beatles]] drummer [[Ringo Starr]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://web2.airmail.net/gshultz/drumhist.html |title=\"The Story Behind Ringo's Drums\" by Charlie West |access-date=2014-11-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727094905/http://web2.airmail.net/gshultz/drumhist.html |archive-date=2019-07-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nProducts manufactured by Ludwig include [[drum kit]]s and [[drum hardware|hardware]]. The company also commercialises other percussion instruments (from the Musser Mallet Company acquired in 1965) such as [[marimba]]s, [[vibraphone]]s, [[xylophone]]s and [[mark tree|bar chimes]] through its [[parent company]] [[Conn-Selmer]].<ref>[https://www.conn-selmer.com/en-us/instruments/educational-percussion/mallet-instruments Mallet instruments] on Conn-Selmer website</ref><ref>[https://www.conn-selmer.com/en-us/our-brands Our brands] on Conn-Selmer website, 11 Nov 2019</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe Ludwig Drum Company was established in 1909 by [[William F. Ludwig, Sr.|William F.]] & Theobald Ludwig, sons of a [[Germany|German]] immigrant to the [[United States]].<ref name=\"ludwig-history\">{{cite web |url=http://www.conn-selmer.com/en-us/about/history/our-brands/ludwig/ |title=Ludwig |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=Our Brands |publisher=Conn-Selmer, Inc. |access-date=2015-12-21 |archive-date=2016-08-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827193517/http://www.conn-selmer.com/en-us/about/history/our-brands/ludwig/}}</ref> William Jr. had been a professional drummer, playing with circuses and touring vaudeville shows, along with the occasional skating-rink gig. Since this work was irregular, he and his brother, Theobald, opened a drum shop in Chicago; they called it Ludwig & Ludwig.<ref name=origins/> The company started with a concept for the design and manufacture of a functional [[bass drum pedal]].<ref name=conn>{{Cite web |url=http://www.conn-selmer.com/en-us/about/history/our-brands/ludwig/ |title=Ludwig on Conn-Selmer website |access-date=2014-11-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141120094821/http://www.conn-selmer.com/en-us/about/history/our-brands/ludwig/ |archive-date=2014-11-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe company added new products to its catalog, such as [[snare drums]] and [[timpani]], in 1916. In 1917, Ludwig signed a deal to build rope drums{{what|date=May 2019}} to support [[World War I]]. Theobald Ludwig died in 1918, and William continued on his own.<ref name=conn/> By 1923, the factory was the largest drum manufacturer in the world, employing 240 workers.<ref name=origins/>\n\nIn the late 1920s, the company was sold to the [[C.G. Conn]] instrument company. William Ludwig stayed on to run the company for Conn (which also owned the Leedy Drum Co. at this time). Eventually, William Ludwig decided to leave Conn and start a new company of his own. He was unable to use the Ludwig name since that trademark now belonged to Conn who continued to market Ludwig & Ludwig drums.\n\n{{multiple image|caption_align=center|header_align=center\n |header= A Ludwig banjo in the Jazz Age\n | align = right\n| image1 = Ludwig Big Chief Banjo (1930), American Banjo Museum.jpg\n | width1 = 154\n | alt1 = Ludwig Big Chief Banjo (1930), American Banjo Museum\n | caption1 = From about 1921 to 1931, Ludwig made banjos, such as the ''Big Chief Banjo'' (1930), displayed at the [[American Banjo Museum]].<ref name=banjo>{{cite web |url= http://www.vintagebanjomaker.com/ludwig/4594323482|title=Makers Alphabetically\u00a0|author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= vintagebanjomaker.com|publisher= |access-date= 13 March 2020|quote=}}</ref>\n\n  | image2 = Body of Ludwig Big Chief banjo (1930) at American Banjo Museum.jpg\n | width2 = 154\n | alt2 = Body of Ludwig Big Chief banjo (1930) at American Banjo Museum\n | caption2  =The ''Big Chief'' banjo was highly decorated, with gold plating, engraving,  and decorative inlayed wood patterns.\n | image3= Back of of Ludwig Big Chief banjo (1930) at American Banjo Museum.jpg\n |width3= 154\n | alt3= Back of Ludwig Big Chief banjo (1930) at American Banjo Museum\n | caption3=The back, in wood inlay. The banjos are highly prized today, but were ultimately a financial failure, [[Great Depression in the United States|the market having disappeared]].<ref name=banjo/>\n }}\n\nIn 1937, William bought a factory building and started The WFL Drum Company (his initials). The company continued producing drums at a small scale for the duration of [[World War II]], but William got back to the idea of making the company a large drum manufacturer after the armistice. WFL was a competitor with Ludwig and Ludwig. Conn combined their two drum brands into one in the early 1950s, forming Leedy & Ludwig, and then decided to quit the drum business altogether. In 1955, William and his son Bill Jr. were able to buy the Ludwig trademark back from Conn, and over the next few years their company and its products transitioned from the WFL brand to being called \"Ludwig\" again.\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = I stopped at that picture and asked why he (Ringo Starr) put our name on the front of his bass drum head. Arbiter said that he was so proud that he had an imported drum set from America, especially from a famous company like Ludwig, that at the time of purchase he insisted on having the Ludwig name painted on the front of the head!\n |source = William Ludwig's grandson<ref name=origins/>\n |width  = 50%\n |align  = right\n}}\nDespite initial success, Ludwig's global breakthrough would occur February 9, 1964, when [[The Beatles]] made their historic American TV debut on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]],''<ref>[http://www.edsullivan.com/the-beatles-on-the-ed-sullivan-show-on-february-9-1964/ \"The Beatles on The Ed Sullivan Show on February 9, 1964\" on Ed Sullivan website]</ref><ref name=bible>[http://www.beatlesbible.com/1964/02/09/the-beatles-first-ed-sullivan-show/ \"The Beatles\u2019 first Ed Sullivan Show\" on The Beatles Bible]</ref>\nand the Ludwig logo, displayed on the front of Ringo Starr's bass drum, could be seen by the television audience of about seventy-three million people.<ref name=hist>[http://www.vintageludwigdrums.com/60shistory.html \"The 1960s\" at Vintage Ludwig Drums]</ref><ref name=origins>[http://www.chicagoreader.com/Bleader/archives/2012/05/07/the-origins-of-ludwig-drums \"The origins of Ludwig drums\" on The Chicago Reader]</ref><ref name=bible/> As it happens, Starr chose that brand upon joining the band simply because he liked the oyster pearl black color of the drum kit he chose. Regardless, the publicity resulted in Ludwig's sales doubling quickly to $13 million, which prompted production to increase to a 24/7 production as the company became the foremost drum manufacturer in North America for twenty years.<ref>{{cite news | last= O'Reilly | first= Terry | title= Bookmarks 2016\n | url= http://www.cbc.ca/radio/undertheinfluence/summer-series-bookmarks-2016-1.3612090 | accessdate=27 August 2016| work= Under the Influence | publisher= CBC News}}</ref>\n\nLudwig acquired the \"Musser Mallet Company\", a manufacturer of [[xylophone]]s, [[marimba]]s and [[vibraphone]]s, in 1965.<ref name=\"ludwig-history\" /> Ludwig was a strong presence in the marching drum market. Their drums along with their [[Slingerland]] rivals.  During the 1970s, Ludwig's \u201cChallenger\u201d line of snare drums offered sophisticated tuning and strong build quality.  Ludwig drums were used by many leading drum and bugle corp.\n\nOn 4 November 1981, William F Ludwig II sold the business to the Selmer Company (now [[Conn-Selmer]]). Selmer closed the Damen Avenue factory in the ensuing years and moved the drum production business to [[Monroe, North Carolina]], in 1984.<ref name=\"ludwig-history\" /><ref name=origins/><ref>[http://www.saxophone.org/museum/saxophones/manufacturer/1/history/0 Selmer's History, 7 Dec 2011]</ref> In 2002, Ludwig merged with [[Conn-Selmer]], becoming a [[brand]] of [[Conn-Selmer]], Inc..<ref>[https://www.ludwig-drums.com/en-us/ludwig/about About: 2000-2009] on Ludwig website</ref>\n\nThe Musser manufacturing facility remained in [[LaGrange, Illinois]], until 2013, and was then moved to [[Elkhart, Indiana]].<ref name=\"musser-history\">{{cite web |url=http://www.conn-selmer.com/en-us/about/history/our-brands/musser/ |title=Musser |author=<!--Staff writers); no by-line.--> |date= |website=Our Brands |publisher=Conn-Selmer |access-date=2015-12-21 |archive-date=2017-10-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005143537/http://www.conn-selmer.com/en-us/about/history/our-brands/musser |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Artists ==\nSome of the musicians that currently or previously played Ludwigs include:<ref>[http://www.ludwig-drums.com/artists.php Artists on Ludwig website]</ref><ref>[http://www.ludwig-drums.com/ludwigDVD.php \"A Century of the most famous names\" on Ludwig website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141121155141/http://www.ludwig-drums.com/ludwigDVD.php |date=2014-11-21 }}</ref>\n{{multiple image\n|align = right\n|direction = vertical\n|total_width = 250\n|header = \n| image1 = 20110626 043 All-Starr-Band-in-Paris Ringo-Starr drums WP.jpg\n| image2   = Alex Van Halen - Van Halen Live.jpg\n| image3   = Marky_Ramone_PalmaDeMallorca_Spain.jpeg\n| footer = From above to below: [[Ringo Starr]], [[Alex Van Halen]] and [[Marky Ramone]], some of the musicians using Ludwig\n}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Jerry Allison]] ([[Buddy Holly & The Crickets]])\n*[[Carmine Appice]]<ref>[http://www.glidemagazine.com/37402/carmen-appice/ \"Carmine Appice, an exclusive interview\"], ''Glide Magazine'', 8 Jul 2013</ref>\n*[[Mick Avory]] ([[Kinks]])\n*[[Ginger Baker]]\n*Derek Ballard ([[A Band Called O]])\n*[[Barriemore Barlow]] ([[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]])\n*[[Frank Beard (musician)|Frank Beard]] ([[ZZ Top]])\n*[[Fred Below]]\n*[[Pete Best]]\n*[[Hal Blaine]]\n*[[Jason Bonham]]\n*[[John Bonham]] ([[Led Zeppelin]])<ref>[http://www.johnbonham.co.uk/drumsetup/drums.html Drum set up on John Bonham website]</ref><ref>[http://www.drummagazine.com/lessons/post/10-ways-to-sound-like-john-bonham/ \"10 Ways To Sound Like John Bonham\" by John Natellion] ''Drum Magazine'', Nov 2008</ref>\n*[[Cindy Blackman]] ([[Lenny Kravitz]])\n*[[Don Brewer]] ([[Grand Funk Railroad]])\n*[[Bill Bruford]] ([[Yes (band)|Yes]], [[King Crimson]], [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], [[Earthworks (band)|Earthworks]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billbruford.com/drums.php|title=Bill Bruford|website=www.billbruford.com|access-date=2017-02-10}}</ref>\n*[[Tony Buck (musician)|Tony Buck]]\n*[[Clive Bunker]] ([[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]])\n*[[Larry Bunker]] (jazz and studio legend)\n*[[Jim Capaldi]] ([[Traffic (band)|Traffic]])\n*[[Eric Carr]] ([[Kiss (band)|KISS]])\n*[[Nameless Ghoul]] ([[Ghost (Swedish band)|Ghost]])\n*[[Luis Cardenas]] ([[Renegade (band)|Renegade]])\n*[[Bun E. Carlos]] ([[Cheap Trick]])\n*[[Karen Carpenter]]\n*[[Vinnie Colaiuta]]\n*[[John Cowsill]] ([[Cowsills]], [[Beach Boys]])\n*[[Mark Craney]] ([[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]])\n*[[Peter Criss]] ([[Kiss (band)|KISS]])\n*[[Dino Danelli]] ([[Young Rascals]])\n*[[John Densmore]] ([[The Doors]])\n*Michael Derosier ([[Heart (band)|Heart]])\n*[[Bobby Elliott]] ([[The Hollies]])\n*[[Gregg Errico]] ([[Sly & The Family Stone]])\n*[https://www.elementaljoe.co.uk/ Rob Finch (Elemental Joe)]\n*[[Mick Fleetwood]] ([[Fleetwood Mac]])\n*[[Roy Haynes]]\n*[[Don Henley]] ([[Eagles (band)|The Eagles]])\n*[[Rob Hirst]] ([[Midnight Oil]])\n*[[Barry Jenkins]] ([[The Animals]])\n* Jimmy Johnson, Jr. ([[Duke Ellington Orchestra]])\n*[[Jo Jones|Papa Jo Jones]]\n*[[Kenney Jones]] ([[Small Faces]] / [[Faces (band)|Faces]])\n*[[Brian Keenan (musician born 1943)|Brian Keenan]] ([[Chambers Brothers]])\n*[[Joey Kramer]] ([[Aerosmith]])\n*[[Bill Kreutzmann]] 