{"title_page": "Dani G\u00fciza", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Gonz\u00e1lez|G\u00fciza}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Dani G\u00fciza\n| image = Danig.jpg\n| image_size = 160\n| caption = G\u00fciza as a [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] player in 2008\n| fullname = Daniel Gonz\u00e1lez G\u00fciza<ref name=Profile>{{cite news|url=https://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/envivos/fichas/1/135/4231.html|title=Daniel Gonz\u00e1lez G\u00dcIZA|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1980|8|17|df=y}}<ref name=Profile2>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/daniel-guiza_prs205984/person.shtml|title=Daniel G\u00fciza|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Jerez de la Frontera]], Spain<ref name=Profile/>\n| height = 1.82 m<ref name=Profile2/>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Striker]]\n| currentclub = [[Atl\u00e9tico Sanluque\u00f1o CF|Atl\u00e9tico Sanluque\u00f1o]]\n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Xerez CD|Xerez]]\n| years1 = 1998\u20131999 | clubs1 = [[Xerez CD|Xerez]] | caps1 = 16 | goals1 = 1\n| years2 = 1999\u20132002 | clubs2 = [[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]] | caps2 = 70 | goals2 = 37\n| years3 = 1999\u20132003 | clubs3 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps3 = 7 | goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 1999\u20132000 | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Dos Hermanas CF|Dos Hermanas]] (loan) | caps4 = 18 | goals4 = 9\n| years5 = 2002\u20132003 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Recreativo de Huelva|Recreativo]] (loan) | caps5 = 4 | goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2003 | clubs6 = \u2192 [[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona B]] (loan) | caps6 = 13 | goals6 = 5\n| years7 = 2003\u20132005 | clubs7 = [[Ciudad de Murcia|Ciudad Murcia]] | caps7 = 81 | goals7 = 36\n| years8 = 2005\u20132007 | clubs8 = [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] | caps8 = 61 | goals8 = 20\n| years9 = 2007\u20132008 | clubs9 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps9 = 37 | goals9 = 27\n| years10 = 2008\u20132011 | clubs10 = [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K. (football)|Fenerbah\u00e7e]] | caps10 = 62 | goals10 = 23\n| years11 = 2011\u20132013 | clubs11 = [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] | caps11 = 32 | goals11 = 3\n| years12 = 2012\u20132013 | clubs12 = \u2192 [[Johor Darul Ta'zim F.C.|Johor Darul Ta'zim]] (loan) | caps12 = 10 | goals12 = 6\n| years13 = 2013\u20132015 | clubs13 = [[Cerro Porte\u00f1o]] | caps13 = 46 | goals13 = 15\n| years14 = 2015\u20132017 | clubs14 = [[C\u00e1diz CF|C\u00e1diz]] | caps14 = 47 | goals14 = 15\n| years15 = 2017\u2013 | clubs15 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Sanluque\u00f1o CF|Atl\u00e9tico Sanluque\u00f1o]] | caps15 = 77 | goals15 = 12\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 2007\u20132010 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps1 = 21 | nationalgoals1 = 6\n| club-update = 7 March 2020\n}}\n'''Daniel Gonz\u00e1lez G\u00fciza''' ({{IPA-es|da\u02c8njel \u02c8\u0263wi\u03b8a}}; born 17 August 1980) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for [[Atl\u00e9tico Sanluque\u00f1o CF]].\n\nA [[late bloomer]], he made a name for himself at the age of 27, being crowned [[La Liga]] top scorer with [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]. Subsequently, he helped the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]] win [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]], and signed with [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K. (football)|Fenerbah\u00e7e]] in Turkey shortly afterwards.\n\nOver eight seasons, G\u00fciza amassed Spanish top division totals of 141 matches and 52 goals, mainly with Mallorca and [[Getafe CF|Getafe]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Early years===\nHaving started playing on the streets of his hometown of [[Jerez de la Frontera]] in [[C\u00e1diz]], G\u00fciza used to hide behind trees in an attempt to avoid the running, despite being then coached by boyhood idol [[Kiko (footballer, born 1972)|Kiko]], who begun his professional career with local [[C\u00e1diz CF]].<ref name=\"LOWE\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/apr/28/realmallorca.laligafootball|title=How dirty Nuria rescued one of Spain's greatest talents|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|first=Sid|last=Lowe|date=28 April 2008|accessdate=18 February 2009}}</ref> He eventually made it into his local club [[Xerez CD]] and, after one season there, first showed his eye for goal at [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] side [[Dos Hermanas CF]], loaned immediately after [[RCD Mallorca]] bought him. Such performances saw him make his debut in [[La Liga]] for the latter at the age of 19, but he would fail to perform, being relegated to [[RCD Mallorca B|the reserves]].<ref name=\"CUE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=775689.html|title=Diamond Guiza right on cue|publisher=FIFA|date=23 May 2008|accessdate=10 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nG\u00fciza was then loaned out to [[Recreativo de Huelva]], but could not find a secure place in the team, and moved soon after to [[FC Barcelona B]], also on loan.<ref name=\"CUE\"/> Subsequently, he joined [[Ciudad de Murcia]] in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]], where his career saw a turning point with two consecutive top-five finishes in the top scorers' list (runner-up in the [[2004\u201305 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2004\u201305 season]]).<ref name=\"CUE\"/>\n\n===Getafe===\nThis impressed [[Bernd Schuster]] enough to sign G\u00fciza for [[Getafe CF]] in the summer of 2005. He was an instant first-choice at his new team and became recognised as a top flight striker, scoring 27 goals in 70 competitive games \u2013 seven in nine [[Copa del Rey]] appearances \u2013 while the team from the [[Madrid]] outskirts achieved back-to-back ninth-league places.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2019/05/06/primera/1557177863_863865.html|title=Semejanzas y diferencias del Getafe de Bordal\u00e1s y el 'Eurogeta'|trans-title=Similarities and differences between Bordal\u00e1s' Getafe and 'Eurogeta'|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|first=Christian|last=Redondo|language=Spanish|date=7 May 2019|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe club's president, \u00c1ngel Torres, described him as \"the best finisher in the first division after [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]]\".<ref name=\"CUE\"/> On 10 May 2007, he was one of three players on target in a 4\u20130 home defeat of [[FC Barcelona]] for [[2006\u201307 Copa del Rey|the semi-finals]] of the [[Copa del Rey]], which meant qualification for the decisive match for the first time ever after a 6\u20135 aggregate win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2007/05/10/futbol/1178822893.html|title=K.O. hist\u00f3rico del Bar\u00e7a|trans-title=Historical Bar\u00e7a K.O.|newspaper=El Mundo|first=Miguel \u00c1ngel|last=Herguedas|language=Spanish|date=10 May 2007|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Mallorca===\nAfter four years, G\u00fciza returned to Mallorca in a [[Euro|\u20ac]]5 million move, brokered by his wife and agent [[Nuria Berm\u00fadez]], experiencing a breakthrough season.<ref name=\"LOWE\"/> On 20 April 2008 he scored a [[hat-trick]] against [[Real Murcia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=685249.html|title=Madrid motor further clear at Racing|publisher=UEFA|date=20 April 2008|accessdate=12 October 2010}}</ref> and finished the campaign as [[2007\u201308 La Liga|the league]]'s top scorer by scoring 27 goals in 37 matches, a feat achieved without a single [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]].<ref name=\"CUE\"/>\n\nClub coach [[Gregorio Manzano]] said: \"In 24 years of coaching I've never had the winner of the ''[[Pichichi Trophy|Pichichi]]'' in my team. Dani is the top goalscorer in our league, and deserves extra credit for doing it without taking penalties, and he is also worthy of selection to Euro 2008\".<ref name=\"CUE\"/>\n\n===Fenerbah\u00e7e===\nOn 8 July 2008, G\u00fciza signed for [[Turkey|Turkish]] club [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K. (football)|Fenerbah\u00e7e SK]] for \u20ac14 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11827_3794030,00.html|title=Fener clinch G\u00fciza deal|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=8 July 2008|accessdate=23 July 2008}}</ref> He managed to score twice in the [[S\u00fcper Lig]] in his first month, adding another two in the team's [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|run]] in the [[UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2008/08/13/mas_futbol/1218578424_850215.html|title=Juve y Arsenal aclaran su camino y G\u00fciza salva al Fenerbah\u00e7e|trans-title=Juve and Arsenal clear their way and G\u00fciza saves Fenerbah\u00e7e|newspaper=Diario AS|language=Spanish|date=13 August 2008|accessdate=19 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jn.pt/desporto/interior/f-c-porto-vence-fenerbahce-3-1-e-lidera-o-grupo-g-1014571.html|title=F. C. Porto vence Fenerbah\u00e7e (3\u20131) e lidera o grupo G|trans-title=F. C. Porto beat Fenerbah\u00e7e (3\u20131) and lead group G|newspaper=[[Jornal de Not\u00edcias]]|language=Portuguese|date=17 September 2008|accessdate=19 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nG\u00fciza ended a long scoring drought on 22 March 2009 with an early goal against [[Bursaspor]], as Fenerbah\u00e7e lost 1\u20132 in the dying minutes of the game. Prior to the beginning of [[2009\u201310 S\u00fcper Lig|2009\u201310]] he put three past [[Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC]] in [[2009\u201310 UEFA Europa League qualifying phase and play-off round#First leg 3|the third qualifying round]] of the [[UEFA Europa League]], in a 5\u20131 home win (6\u20132 on aggregate),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2009/07/31/mas_futbol/1249021642_850215.html|title=Tres goles de G\u00fciza con el Fenerbah\u00e7e|trans-title=Three G\u00fciza goals with Fenerbah\u00e7e|newspaper=Diario AS|language=Spanish|date=31 July 2009|accessdate=19 February 2018}}</ref> netting his first in the domestic competition in matchday one against [[Denizlispor]], in the first minute of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fenerbahce.org/eng/detay.asp?|title=Denizlispor 0\u20132 Fenerbahce|publisher=Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K|date=10 August 2009|accessdate=10 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring his first two seasons in [[Istanbul]], G\u00fciza helped the team to consecutive [[Turkish Cup]] finals, netting in the [[2008\u201309 Turkish Cup|2008\u201309 edition]] in a 2\u20134 loss against [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K|Be\u015fikta\u015f JK]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/deportes/2009/05/14/fenerbahce-luis-aragones-pierde-final-copa-turquia/0003_7716811.htm|title=El Fenerbah\u00e7e de Luis Aragon\u00e9s pierde la final de la Copa de Turqu\u00eda|trans-title=Luis Aragon\u00e9s' Fenerbah\u00e7e lose Turkish Cup final|newspaper=[[La Voz de Galicia]]|language=Spanish|date=14 May 2009|accessdate=19 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Getafe===\nOn 18 August 2011, one day after his 31st birthday, G\u00fciza signed with former club Getafe for \u20ac6 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kap.gov.tr/yay/Bildirim/Bildirim.aspx?id=166671|title=\u00d6zel Durum A\u00e7\u0131klamas\u0131 (Genel)|trans-title=Disclosure of exception (general)|publisher=Turkish Public Disclosure System|language=Turkish|date=18 August 2011|accessdate=30 August 2011}}</ref> agreeing to a three-year contract shortly after. He was regularly played in [[2011\u201312 La Liga|the first season in his second spell]], starting in 15 of his appearances, but failed to reproduce his previous form and scored just three goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/getafe-cf/271238.html|title=Yo jugu\u00e9 en el Getafe: Dani G\u00fciza|trans-title=I played for Getafe: Dani G\u00fciza|publisher=[[Vavel]]|first=Carlos|last=Fern\u00e1ndez|language=Spanish|date=16 October 2013|accessdate=19 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 November 2012, G\u00fciza signed for [[Malaysia Super League]] side [[Johor Darul Ta'zim F.C.]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-my/news/3896/malaysia/2012/11/06/3505864/official-guiza-joins-johor-on-loan|title=Official: Guiza joins Johor on loan|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|first=Prem|last=Kumar|date=6 November 2012|accessdate=6 November 2012}}</ref> His move, along with the acquisition of former [[S.S. Lazio]] winger [[Simone Del Nero]] and seven [[Malaysia national football team|Malaysian internationals]], was part of the club's major restructuring plans upon the appointment of [[Tunku Ismail Idris]], the Crown Prince of [[Johor]], as president;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.malaysiandigest.com/sports/185182-johor-sign-safee-sali-on-one-year-loan.html|title=Johor sign Safee Sali on one-year loan|newspaper=Malaysian Digest|date=5 December 2012|accessdate=2 February 2013}}</ref> based on past achievements and honours the player, at the time of his signing, was arguably the most prolific footballer to have competed in the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://my.news.yahoo.com/blogs/fit-to-post-sports/daniel-guiza-real-deal-160748758.html|title=\u2018Euro 2008 star Daniel Guiza is the real deal\u2019|publisher=[[Yahoo! News]]|first=Damon|last=Yeo|date=8 November 2012|accessdate=2 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nG\u00fciza made his first competitive appearance and league debut for his new team on 8 January 2013, in an opening day away game against [[Pahang FA]]: despite a 2\u20133 defeat, he provided the [[Assist (football)|assists]] for both of his side's goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnstar.com/football/m-league/news/detail/item917610/Darul-Takzim-left-stunned-by-Pahang/|title=Darul Takzim left stunned by Pahang|publisher=[[ESPN Star Sports]]|date=9 January 2013|accessdate=11 January 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130215235520/http://www.espnstar.com/football/m-league/news/detail/item917610/Darul-Takzim-left-stunned-by-Pahang/|archivedate=15 February 2013}}</ref> He scored his first competitive goal on 15 January in an away game against treble-winners [[Kelantan FA]], with an expertly curled [[Direct free kick|free-kick]] from 25 yards out as the game ended 1\u20131;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnstar.com/home/news/detail/item920238/Kelantan,-Darul-Takzim-share-spoils/|title=Kelantan, Johor Darul Takzim FC share spoils|publisher=ESPN Star Sports|date=15 January 2013|accessdate=26 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924013107/http://www.espnstar.com/home/news/detail/item920238/Kelantan,-Darul-Takzim-share-spoils/|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> three days later he netted from open play in a home game against [[2012 Malaysia Cup]] runners-up [[ATM FA]], with a volleyed lob from the edge of the penalty area in an eventual 2\u20132 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-sg/match/100614/johor-fc-vs-atm-fa/report|title=Johor Darul Takzim 2\u20132 ATM: Southern Tigers made to sweat for a point against Gladiators|publisher=Goal|date=18 January 2013|accessdate=6 December 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130216041011/http://www.goal.com/en-sg/match/100614/johor-fc-vs-atm-fa/report|archive-date=16 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nG\u00fciza played his last match for Darul Takzim on 6 April 2013 in a [[2013 Malaysia FA Cup|1\u20132 loss]] against [[Selangor FA]] in the [[Malaysia FA Cup|FA Cup]], after his loan was ended prematurely.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-my/news/3986/editorial/2013/04/07/3883702/adios-dani-guiza-youve-been-a-blessing-to-malaysian-football|title=Adios Dani Guiza, you've been a blessing to Malaysian football!|publisher=Goal|first=Nicolas|last=Anil|date=7 April 2013|accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref> Both he and Del Nero left the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sports247.my/2013/03/now-guizas-leaving/|title=Now Guiza\u2019s leaving|publisher=Sports 247|first=Rizal|last=Abdullah|date=31 March 2013|accessdate=7 April 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403093301/http://www.sports247.my/2013/03/now-guizas-leaving/|archivedate=3 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/sport/football-malaysia-s-johor-cuts-guiza-loo/629080.html|title=Malaysia's Johor cuts G\u00fciza loose mid-season|publisher=[[Channel NewsAsia]]|date=8 April 2013|accessdate=8 April 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130628205736/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/sport/football-malaysia-s-johor-cuts-guiza-loo/629080.html|archive-date=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Cerro Porte\u00f1o===\nIn 2013, G\u00fciza joined [[Cerro Porte\u00f1o]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2013/07/29/internacional/1375116708_282851.html|title=G\u00fciza ficha por el Cerro Porte\u00f1o de Paraguay por una temporada|trans-title=G\u00fciza signs for Cerro Porte\u00f1o from Paraguay for one season|newspaper=Diario AS|first=Quique|last=Rubio|language=Spanish|date=29 July 2013|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> He made his debut on 14 September of that year, as a 69th-minute substitute against [[Sportivo Carapegu\u00e1]], scoring four minutes later in an eventual 4\u20130 home win<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.com.py/deportes/futbol/giza-contento-por-el-debut-618090.html|title=G\u00fciza, contento por su debut con el Cicl\u00f3n|trans-title=G\u00fciza, happy with debut with the Cyclone|newspaper=[[ABC Color]]|language=Spanish|date=14 September 2013|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> as the team went on to win its 30th [[Paraguayan Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] title.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/11/25/futbol/futbol_internacional/resto_de_america/1385403075.html|title=Dani G\u00fciza, campe\u00f3n con el Cerro Porte\u00f1o paraguayo|trans-title=Dani G\u00fciza, champion with Paraguay's Cerro Porte\u00f1o|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|first=Dino|last=Cappelli|language=Spanish|date=25 November 2013|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> He also featured in [[2014 Copa Libertadores|the following year]]'s [[Copa Libertadores]], netting three times to help to progress from the group stage and leading to interest from other clubs, to which he responded: \"My heart is here, from day one they have shown me affection, my heart is what drives me, so I'm staying here\"; however, new manager [[Leonardo Astrada]] did not have the player in his plans, which led to his release in March 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2015/03/12/futbol/futbol_internacional/resto_de_america/1426173894.html|title=Dani G\u00fciza ya es historia en Cerro Porte\u00f1o|trans-title=Dani G\u00fciza is already history at Cerro Porte\u00f1o|newspaper=Marca|first=Dino|last=Cappelli|language=Spanish|date=12 March 2015|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===C\u00e1diz===\nIn August 2015, G\u00fciza returned to his native Andalusia, signing for C\u00e1diz. His arrival drew the ire of fans, due to disparaging remarks he had made about the club a decade ago while playing for local rivals Xerez.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/new-cadiz-signing-dani-guiza-6187405|title=New Cadiz signing Dani Guiza told to \"DIE\" by fans after uncovering 2005 comments about club|newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]]|first=Aaron|last=Flanagan|date=3 August 2015|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 June 2016, G\u00fciza scored the only goal at [[H\u00e9rcules CF]] in the second leg of the [[2016 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B playoffs|play-off finals]] (2\u20130 on aggregate), helping the team return to the second division after six years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canalsur.es/inicio/0-1-giza-devuelve-al-cadiz-a-segunda/906119.html|title=0\u20131. Dani G\u00fciza asciende al C\u00e1diz|trans-title=0\u20131. Dani G\u00fciza promotes C\u00e1diz|publisher=[[Canal Sur]]|language=Spanish|date=26 June 2016|accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref> On 4 July of the following year, after appearing sparingly during [[2016\u201317 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the season]], he left.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cadizcf.com/noticia/hasta-pronto-a-dani-guiza|title='Hasta pronto' a Dani G\u00fciza|trans-title='See you soon' to Dani G\u00fciza|publisher=C\u00e1diz CF|language=Spanish|date=4 July 2017|accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Atl\u00e9tico Sanluque\u00f1o===\nOn 10 July 2017, the 37-year-old G\u00fciza signed a two-year contract for [[Atl\u00e9tico Sanluque\u00f1o CF]], [[2016\u201317 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|recently relegated]] to [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atleticosanluquenocf.com/index.php/noticias/competicion/230-el-atletico-sanluqueno-cf-ficha-a-gueiza-para-la-proxima-temporada|title=El Atl\u00e9tico Sanluque\u00f1o CF ficha a G\u00fciza para la pr\u00f3xima temporada|trans-title=Atl\u00e9tico Sanluque\u00f1o CF sign G\u00fciza for next season|publisher=Atl\u00e9tico Sanluque\u00f1o|language=Spanish|date=July 2017|accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Spain Euro 08 celebration 1.jpg|thumb|right|240px|[[Fernando Torres]], G\u00fciza and [[Cesc F\u00e0bregas]] celebrating after their success at Euro 2008.]]\nG\u00fciza was a [[late bloomer]] on the international stage, having been first called up by [[Spain national football team|Spain]] on 8 November 2007 (aged 27) for [[UEFA Euro 2008]] [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying|qualifiers]] against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] and [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]], as the national team was already qualified for the finals in [[Austria]] and [[Switzerland]]. He made his international debut against the latter on 21 November, in a 1\u20130 home win in [[Las Palmas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=197489&cc=5739&league=UEFA.EUROQ|title=Spain 1\u20130 Northern Ireland: Spain end Irish hopes|publisher=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]]|date=21 November 2007|accessdate=18 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nG\u00fciza was subsequently selected to the final squad of 23 but, despite being the league's top scorer in that year, still doubted his chances of being picked: \"I was really scared I'd miss out, because being the league's top scorer doesn't guarantee you a place\".<ref name=\"CUE\"/> On 18 June 2008 he made his debut in the tournament, and scored Spain's winning goal against [[Greece national football team|Greece]] during the dying moments of the last match group stage match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=232279&cc=5739&league=UEFA.EURO|title=Greece 1\u20132 Spain: G\u00fciza seals Spanish hat-trick|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=18 June 2008|accessdate=18 February 2009}}</ref> In the quarter-finals he came on as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] against [[Italy national football team|Italy]], missing the team's fourth attempt in an eventual [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=232283&cc=5739&league=UEFA.EURO|title=Spain beat Italy in penalty shootout|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=22 June 2008|accessdate=18 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn the semi-final match against [[Russia national football team|Russia]], G\u00fciza netted his second international goal, in a 3\u20130 win: after receiving a pass from [[Cesc F\u00e0bregas]], he quickly side-flicked it over the goalkeeper.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=232285&cc=5739&league=UEFA.EURO|title=Spain 3\u20130 Russia: Fabregas proves the inspiration|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=26 June 2008|accessdate=18 February 2009}}</ref> He played 15 minutes in [[UEFA Euro 2008 Final|the final]] against [[Germany national football team|Germany]] after replacing [[Fernando Torres]] (who scored the game's only goal), and came very close to assisting [[Marcos Senna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2008/7363545.stm|title=Germany 0\u20131 Spain|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=29 June 2008|accessdate=18 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 October 2008, G\u00fciza came on as a late substitute against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], and soon after assisted [[David Villa]] who scored the winning goal in a close 2\u20131 contest for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualifiers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=236431&cc=5739&league=FIFA.WORLDQ.UEFA|title=Villa maintains perfect record|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=15 October 2008|accessdate=18 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nAfter an article circulated in January 2009 involving details about personal life and behaviour in training, G\u00fciza's international career future was questioned.<ref name=\"JEOPARDY\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2009/02/25/1127339/g\u00fcizas-international-career-in-jeopardy|title=G\u00fciza's international career in jeopardy|publisher=Goal|first=Luis|last=Mira|date=25 February 2009|accessdate=8 March 2009}}</ref> Such reports on his behaviour became debatable due to the unreliable sources and any rumours of him being dropped from the Spain team were put to rest when [[Vicente del Bosque]] called him up for his services for the 2010 World Cup qualification matches against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]], where he solidified his superb performance against Belgium, once again coming on in the dying minutes and assisting a last-minute winner during the match held in Istanbul.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2009/04/02/1187603/spain-heroes-guiza-riera-we-have-one-foot-in-the-world-cup|title=Spain heroes Guiza &amp; Riera: We have one foot in the World Cup|publisher=Goal|first=KS|last=Leong|date=2 April 2009|accessdate=6 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 June 2009, G\u00fciza was selected to the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2009/06/01/1298861/spain-name-mata-riera-busquets-and-injured-stars|title=Spain name Mata, Riera, Busquets and injured stars|publisher=Goal|first=Lucas|last=Brown|date=1 June 2009|accessdate=1 June 2009}}</ref> On the 28th he came from the bench as the national team trailed hosts [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] (0\u20131) in the third-place match, and responded with a spectacular brace in the last two minutes as Spain eventually won the game in [[Overtime (sports)|extra-time]] (3\u20132).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/8118574.stm|title=Spain 3\u20132 South Africa (aet)|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 June 2009|accessdate=19 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nG\u00fciza also played for the [[Andalusia autonomous football team|Andalusia autonomous team]] on 27 December 2006, scoring twice in a 3\u20131 win over a combined [[Israel national football team|Israel]]\u2013[[Palestine national football team|Palestine]] side at the [[Estadio de La Cartuja]] in Seville.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eldia.com/nota/2006-12-28-partido-de-futbol-por-la-paz-une-a-israelies-y-palestinos|title=Partido de f\u00fatbol por la paz une a israel\u00edes y palestinos|trans-title=Football match for peace unites Israelis and Palestinians|newspaper=[[El D\u00eda (La Plata)|El D\u00eda]]|language=Spanish|date=28 December 2006|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:NURIA BERMUDEZ REDU.jpg|thumb|175px|G\u00fciza's partner and agent, [[Nuria Berm\u00fadez]].]]\nHe was introduced as \"the greatest promise in Spain\", but also \"the greatest party-goer\" when he first joined Ciudad de Murcia, with club coach [[Juan Manuel Lillo]] stating that he had \"too many birds flying round in his head\".<ref name=\"LOWE\"/>\n\nG\u00fciza suffered a divorce from his first wife Roc\u00edo with whom he had his first child, which gained a lot of publicity in the Spanish press. Furthermore, he admitted that \"the night confuses me\" and, after joining Getafe, he started to take advantage of the night life in [[Madrid]], suffering a [[stomach]] infection as a result and subsequently being forced to go on a diet consisting of liquids alone.<ref name=\"LOWE\"/>\n\nDuring his time at Getafe, G\u00fciza met [[Nuria Berm\u00fadez]]. She sat for the qualifications to become an official [[FIFA]] football agent, which she passed scoring 29 points, just five below the top and went on to become G\u00fciza's agent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/papel/2006/04/16/cronica/1957995_impresora.html|title=De amante a agente de jugadores|trans-title=From lover to players' agent|newspaper=El Mundo|language=Spanish|date=16 April 2006|accessdate=10 February 2009}}</ref> She also obtained the highest score for a female football agent in Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoymujer.com/famosos/famosillos/Nuria,Bermudez,25053,02,2007.html|title=Nuria Berm\u00fadez|publisher=Hoy Mujer|language=Spanish|date=16 February 2007|accessdate=10 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking of his relationship with the [[Model (person)|model]], Getafe coach Schuster said: \"Ever since Dani's been with Nuria, he turns up to training and it doesn't look like he's slept under a bridge\". On 1 December 2007, Berm\u00fadez gave birth to G\u00fciza's second son, also named Daniel, at ''Policl\u00ednica Miramar'' in [[Palma, Majorca]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elperiodico.com/es/gente/20071202/nace-el-hijo-del-futbolista-guiza-y-nuria-bermudez-5502219|title=Nace el hijo del futbolista G\u00fciza y Nuria Berm\u00fadez|trans-title=Son of footballer G\u00fciza and Nuria Berm\u00fadez is born|newspaper=[[El Peri\u00f3dico de Catalunya]]|language=Spanish|date=2 December 2007|accessdate=19 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nBefore Euro 2008, G\u00fciza promised the media that if he were to win the competition, he would then propose to Berm\u00fadez.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/EN/Articolo.aspx?ContenutoId=755444|title=Guiza to propose if Spain win|publisher=Goal|first=Chris|last=Myson|date=29 June 2008|accessdate=6 December 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080815032620/http://www.goal.com/en/Articolo.aspx?ContenutoId=755444|archivedate=15 August 2008}}</ref> In January 2009, the Spanish media began to publicise problems between his family and Berm\u00fadez, with his mother apparently threatening to slit Berm\u00fadez's throat for being a \"thief\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.periodistadigital.com/gente.php/2009/01/18/la-madre-de-dani-guiza-amenaza-con-corta|title=La madre de Dani G\u00fciza amenaza con cortarle el pescuezo a Nuria Berm\u00fadez|trans-title=Dani G\u00fciza's mother threatens to slit Nuria Berm\u00fadez's neck|publisher=Periodista Digital|language=Spanish|date=18 January 2009|accessdate=10 February 2009}}</ref> Berm\u00fadez then left Turkey with son Daniel, amongst claims the latter was ignored by the father.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elblogdefamosas.com/2009/01/26/el-culebron-de-nuria-bermudez/|title=El culebr\u00f3n de Nuria Bermudez|trans-title=Nuria Bermudez's soap opera|publisher=El Blog de Famosas|language=Spanish|date=26 January 2009|accessdate=10 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nG\u00fciza's ex-wife, Roc\u00edo Aranda, revealed that the two had met up just hours before the start of the match between [[England national football team|England]] and Spain on 11 February 2009. According to Aranda, they met up in the hotel bar and went on to have sexual intercourse in one of the bedrooms. Subsequently, it was rumoured that Spain coach Del Bosque would drop him from the team.<ref name=\"JEOPARDY\"/> G\u00fciza spoke against this in an interview with ''[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]'' saying: \"The truth is, I hadn't seen my son in a while so I went to see him in the hotel, I have to take advantage of such opportunities to see my children. To make money, she [his ex-wife] makes up stories. I spoke with [[Fernando Hierro|Hierro]] and I explained the situation. I told him that I had to see my son and I wanted to be with him. I explained everything. I tried my best to be with my son and the truth is the whole story has not come out well in the press.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2009/03/18/futbol/futbol_internacional/espanoles_mundo/1237392236.html|title=G\u00fciza: \"\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no va a ir Ra\u00fal a la selecci\u00f3n si se lo merece como el que m\u00e1s?\"|trans-title=G\u00fciza: \"Why would Ra\u00fal not be selected to the national team if he merits as much as the next guy?\"|newspaper=Marca|first=Jos\u00e9 F\u00e9lix|last=D\u00edaz|language=Spanish|date=18 March 2009|accessdate=18 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|23 September 2019}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.joueurs.daniel.guiza.9790.en.html|title=Daniel G\u00fciza|publisher=Footballdatabase|accessdate=23 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!rowspan=\"2\"|{{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|[[Xerez CD|Xerez]]\n|[[1998\u201399 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1998\u201399]]\n|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n|16||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||16||1\n|<ref name=\"bdfutbol\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/j/j487.html|title=G\u00fciza: Daniel Gonz\u00e1lez G\u00fciza|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Dos Hermanas CF|Dos Hermanas]] (loan)\n|[[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1999\u201300]]\n|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B\n|18||9||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||19||9\n|<ref name=\"bdfutbol\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]]\n|[[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1999\u201300]]\n|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B\n|17||9||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||17||9\n|<ref name=\"bdfutbol\"/>\n|-\n|[[2000\u201301 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2000\u201301]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B\n|28||19||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"